(36, 'SYSJ051', 'Ahmed Saif Eldeen', 'ahmedsaifeldeen1314@gmail.com', '01091310012', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-08-13', 'STEM', 'Rising Senior', '4.0', '', 'ads', 'sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad ', 'sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad ', 'sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad sad sad sadsad sad ', 5, 'lklj', 'jklj', NULL, NULL, 'under_review', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-06-25 14:59:08', NULL, 1, NULL),
(37, 'SYSJ0222', 'Bolat Leila', 'leilabolat8@gmail.com', '+77020513681', 'Kazakhstan', 'female', '2007-04-04', 'Gap', 'Gap', '4.67/5.0(last 4 years)', 'Biology,Medicine & Public Health,Neuroscience & Neurobiology', '-', '“2000Diseases from A to Z - a one-volume clinical reference book.\r\nI was three years old when I first held this giant book and started giggling about some upside-down texts. Looking back, my parents get caught up in nostalgia and laugh, however, they also cautioned me not to touch something that was beyond my understanding.\r\nA never stood for A - an apple for me. Instead, “A - abscess, is a buildup of pus that can affect parts of your body” - the paragraph that glued into my memory.\r\nAs a professional TVshow binge-watcher, you can’t imagine my excitement when Dr.Copoor mentioned an “abscess” in the show “New Amsterdam”, it made me feel powerful and capable of understanding something so valuable. However, as I watched Greys Anatomy, I needed to keep up and my hand was scrolling over the pages of my alphabet every second, allowing me to empathize with patients and physicians.\r\n“P - Parkinson’s” - the word I stumbled upon not from a TVshow, but from a family gathering. This time, I wanted to explore its contents and learn about the mysterious P from its pages.\r\nThe book opened the possibility to take action. For similar individuals, I gathered a community of med-passionate students. Helping them to further their knowledge by inviting and learning from top-notch experts in the medical field. I didnt join, but d the community that they and I needed all along.\r\nAt YSJ , Im eager to continue making big things from something so invaluable.', 'Hello dear team 123,\r\nI noticed that you didnt submit yesterdays task. I understand that writing any research is difficult and delicate. If you have any questions or want my help, please reach out!! Your new deadline is midnight, but open for changes to make the transitions smooth. \r\nYour mentor Leila', 'Youth Science Journal – Researcher(August 2023 - September 2023) https://www.ys-journal.org/issues/issue_10?article=21 \r\n1. Research with an international mentor about the future of 3D bioprinting in Tissue Engineering. Interviewed specialists, and physicians for the data. Paper is considered one of the best out of the tens, and was ed to be published. Got published in the Youth Science Journal Issue 10, July 2024. 2885 words, 7 pages.\r\n\r\n2. STEMulate – Researcher (July 2024 - September 2024)\r\nResearch with a mentor from the Nazarbayev University School of Medicine about migraines and their effects on cognitive abilities in human brains. Literature Review using 2 papers. Read over 10+ papers for the data. Presented the research at the symposium for experts and classmates. 3069 words, 10 pages.\r\n\r\n3. Girls in Research - Researcher(August 2024 - May 2025)\r\nLiterature review about HIV viruses in Alzheimers brain With Phd mentor from Imperial College London. 8622 words, 21 pages.\r\n', 15, 'None', 'Instagram', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-06-25 20:15:48', '{\"Biology\":\"7\",\"Medicine & Public Health\":\"8\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"10\"}', 0, 'Neuroscience & Neurobiology'),
(38, 'SYSJ0191', 'Fatma Mohamed', 'fm700653@gmail.com', '01005285939', 'مصر', 'female', '2000-12-10', 'Kean university ', '2023', '3.5', 'Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy,Computer Science,Data Science,Economics,Education,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)', '3.5', 'Mentorship in research is about knowing the subject and encouraging students when they face challenges. My background in scientific research has helped me do both. I’ve learned to break down difficult ideas and explain them in a clear, supportive way, which I believe matches the standards at York St John University.\r\nMy academic goal at YSJ is to deepen my research expertise while also becoming a more effective mentor. I want to contribute to a collaborative research culture where students feel encouraged to ask questions, make mistakes, and build resilience. I believe YSJ’s emphasis on personal guidance, hands-on supervision, and interdisciplinary research will give me the tools to do this. Being part of a vibrant and supportive research community will help me grow into a mentor who not only shares knowledge but also nurtures students’ confidence and excitement.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor example, I once helped a classmate who was confused by data analysis. Together, we tackled the problem one small step at a time. I saw them gain more confidence as they practiced, and they became genuinely interested in their research. In another case, I supported a group as they d questions for a literature review, helping them focus on new and exciting ideas.\r\n\r\nI want to do the same at YSJ — help students face challenges with patience, build their skills, and become excited about their research. With the supportive culture at YSJ, I believe I can grow into a mentor who helps students reach their potential. \r\n\r\n', 'Hi team 123,\r\n\r\nJust a quick reminder that your Research Idea Proposal was due and we still haven’t received it. I understand you’re all juggling a lot right now, but meeting deadlines is an important part of the research process.\r\n\r\nPlease make it a priority to finalize and submit the proposal by the end of this week. Let me know if you need any support — I’m here to help if you’re stuck or need guidance.\r\n\r\nKeep up the effort, and let’s make sure we stay on track', 'My research background lies at the intersection of data science, machine learning, and educational technology. I hold a Bachelor’s degree in Computer Science and a Master’s degree in Data Analytics, which have given me a strong foundation in data manipulation, statistical modeling, and predictive algorithms. Throughout my academic and professional career, I have focused on applying data-driven solutions to real-world problems and helping organizations leverage insights to make informed decisions.\r\n\r\nI have worked on several collaborative research projects, including one that examined the impact of personalized learning paths on student success rates. In this project, I conducted data preprocessing and built predictive models to identify the most effective learning strategies. The findings were presented at the [Your University] Research Symposium and were later published as a co-authored article in the Journal of Educational Data Mining.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I contributed to a team project on sentiment analysis using deep learning techniques to classify public opinion on educational policies, which we presented at the International Conference on Machine Learning Applications. Beyond these projects, I have also been involved in smaller research initiatives, including applying computer vision to learning resources and developing open-source tools to support reproducible data workflows.\r\n\r\nOverall, my research experiences have equipped me with practical expertise in data analysis, machine learning, and research communication — all of which I aim to continue developing in future projects.', 20, '12: 5', 'facebook', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-06-26 07:32:32', '{\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"5\",\"Computer Science\":\"5\",\"Data Science\":\"5\",\"Economics\":\"5\",\"Education\":\"5\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"5\"}', 0, NULL),
(39, 'SYSJ0243', '', '', '', '', 'female', '2009-08-29', 'STEM', 'G11', '3.8', 'Biology,Education,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering),Medicine & Public Health,Neuroscience & Neurobiology', '', 'Mentorship in scientific research is more than offering academic support it is about cultivating curiosity, resilience, and critical thinking. I strongly resonate with the idea that effective mentors must both understand scientific concepts deeply and inspire students to persevere through challenges. My experience in a STEM high school has allowed me to develop in both of these areas sharpening my own scientific understanding while learning how to support others on their academic journeys.\r\n\r\nBeing part of a STEM based environment has meant constant exposure to research-driven projects and inquiry based learning. Through national competitions and collaborative projects, I’ve learned how to dissect complex problems, communicate scientific ideas clearly, and adapt when experiments don’t go as planned. These experiences not only strengthened my grasp of the scientific process but also taught me how to guide peers who were struggling, whether with formulating hypotheses, analyzing data, or managing frustration when results fell short of expectations.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to continue developing in fields such as environmental science or applied physics, but my mentoring goal is equally significant: I want to support young researchers in gaining confidence in their voice and ideas. I believe science should feel accessible, not intimidating. Programs like YSJ offer the perfect ecosystem for that vision an environment where scientific thought is nurtured and young minds are empowered to publish and grow.\r\n\r\nOne instance that reflects this mindset was during a school-wide climate innovation challenge. While collaborating with a team, I noticed one of our members was struggling with data interpretation and losing interest. I took the initiative to break down the statistical concepts and relate them to real-world climate examples. Not only did that help her understand the material, but it also reignited her excitement for the project. We ended up finishing in the top ranks, but more importantly, she continued exploring data science after the challenge.\r\n\r\nYSJ’s standards align with my values rigor, clarity, and mentorship. I see myself not just as a learner, but as a future mentor who can help bridge the gap between scientific knowledge and student empowerment. I am eager to contribute to a space where young researchers can navigate complexity with courage, supported by peers who believe in their potential', 'Team 123 .....\r\nI hope youre all doing well. I noticed that your Research Idea Proposal hasn’t been submitted yet, and the deadline has already passed. Timelines are crucial for keeping the publication process smooth and fair for everyone, so I want to gently but firmly remind you to prioritize finishing and submitting your proposal as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nIf there’s something holding you back—uncertainty about your idea, team coordination issues, or anything else, please reach out. I’m here to support you. Let’s aim to have it in within the next 48 hours so we can move forward.\r\n\r\nLooking forward to your response. Youve got this!\r\n\r\n Mai Ashraf,\r\nYSJ Senior Researcher', 'My interest in scientific research stems from a deep curiosity about how the world works and a drive to explore real-world challenges through evidence-based thinking. Over the past few years, I’ve engaged in various research driven projects that have allowed me to build a solid foundation in analytical reasoning, data interpretation, and academic communication.\r\n\r\nOne of my most formative experiences involved working on a team project that focused on climate-related solutions. I was responsible for designing and analyzing the data behind an energy-saving prototype. While it wasn’t a formal publication, the experience taught me how to think like a researcher—how to ask meaningful questions, remain open to iteration, and communicate findings clearly to different audiences. We presented the project at a regional showcase and received recognition for the clarity and creativity of our approach.\r\n\r\nBeyond that, I’ve explored smaller, self initiated investigations in fields such as behavioral science, where I examined how digital distractions affect student focus. This experience sparked my interest in interdisciplinary research and helped me appreciate the importance of designing ethical and effective methodologies.\r\n\r\nCurrently, I’m also studying German at a C1 level, which allows me to access a wider range of academic material and has strengthened my scientific writing skills. I see research as a way to contribute thoughtfully to global conversations, and I’m eager to keep growing as both a thinker and a communicator through opportunities like YSJ.\r\n\r\n', 5, 'School will start in about three months', 'from the site ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-06-28 18:58:04', '{\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Education\":\"5\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"5\",\"Medicine & Public Health\":\"10\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"10\"}', 0, NULL),
(40, 'SYSJ0284', 'Radwa Mohammed Refeay', 'radwa.2223522@stemsharkya.moe.edu.eg', '01011837558', 'Egypt', 'female', '2007-09-04', 'STEM School', '2025', '3.75', 'Biology,Chemistry,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering),Environmental Science,Physics & Astrophysics', '', 'Scientific mentorship is not just about becoming adept at some concepts its about demonstrating empathy—when to say and when not to say anything, when to push and when to just listen. On my research journey, I have come to appreciate that good mentorship does not give someone all the answers if anything, it steers someone toward finding their own.\r\n\r\nI have had some experience with scientific inquiry by participating in programs such as ISEF (twice), the Imperial College Research Program, and RISE Research Scholars. I think I have had experience in every aspect and step of scientific inquiry, from formulating research questions to data interpretation, and effective dissemination of results. Having passed through these processes has make me capable of breaking down complex concepts and presenting them in a clear and inspiring way to everyone.\r\n\r\nOne of my roles, and hopes, as a mentor is to help develop curiosity based thinking, while also supporting younger students to push through obstacles of the scientific endeavour. Moreover, my leadership role as Vice President of the admissions club at my school has taught me how to lead, organize, and motivate. During LaunchX I had to work with groups of people that I had never met and within some of those teams I mentored peers on simplifying biotechnical problem solving while we were all operating under some pressure.\r\n\r\nYSJ represents an ideal opportunity for me to foster my scientific leadership skills. The focus on collaboration, peer learning, and open access are big reasons I want to apply because those values are very aligned with everything I have been thinking about for the future.', 'Hi Team 123  \r\nI noticed that your research idea proposal is still pending and the deadline has officially passed. I know things can get busy, but staying on track is super important, especially in research. Let’s not lose momentum now! \r\n\r\nIf you are stuck or unsure how to move forward, please reach out—Iam here to help. Let’s aim to finalize and submit it by this day. You’ve got amazing potential, and I know this project can be something great if we stay focused .\r\n\r\nCheering you on!\r\nRadwa – YSJ SR\r\n\r\n', '\r\nMy research journey began with a deep curiosity about the human body and a strong desire to explore the intersection between science and innovation. Over the past two years, I’ve been actively involved in biomedical research, focusing on immune-related conditions and overlooked biological structures. Most notably, I presented at the Intel ISEF science fair twice, where I proposed a project on the potential therapeutic role of the appendix in autoimmune diseases such as psoriasis. I am currently developing this project further for a third ISEF submission.\r\n\r\nI was accepted into the Imperial College London Research Program, where I gained insights into advanced lab procedures and research ethics. Additionally, I took part in the RISE Research Scholars Program and the IYRC (International Youth Research Conference) with full financial aid, both of which sharpened my understanding of hypothesis formulation, data interpretation, and collaborative writing.\r\n\r\nDuring the NASA Space Apps Challenge, I collaborated with a diverse team to propose a solution combining environmental science and AI, which was shortlisted among top entries. I’ve also participated in math-focused research challenges such as IYMC and IBB, where I analyzed real-world problems using interdisciplinary approaches.\r\n\r\nIn 2023, I co-authored a project presented at the Global Goals Youth Summit, focusing on youth-driven healthcare innovation. I’ve also been ed to represent Egypt at an international science diplomacy forum in Japan, based on my contributions to global scientific discussions.\r\n\r\nThese diverse experiences have solidified my passion for research and prepared me to both lead and collaborate in multidisciplinary environments. I’m now especially interested in projects that bridge biomedical research, public health, and data science to generate scalable solutions.', 5, 'The start of July until end of August ', 'From Google Search', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-01 03:53:12', '{\"Biology\":\"6\",\"Chemistry\":\"6\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"8\",\"Environmental Science\":\"8\",\"Physics & Astrophysics\":\"7\"}', 0, 'Aerospace Engineering'),
(42, 'SYSJ0254', 'Asmaa Hossam', 'asmaahossam289@gmail.com', '01014717368', 'Egypt', 'female', '2005-09-28', 'Beni Swif University', '2nd', '3.79', '', '2nd of Aerospace Engineering', 'Mentorship in scientific research is more than just providing knowledge it is also about instilling curiosity, resilience, and a sense of purpose in the face of challenging scientific obstacles.  As an international award-winning researcher and the youngest judge at international science fairs such as ISEF and IEEE YESIST12, I have learned that effective mentorship begins with empathy and a thorough understanding of scientific principles, both of which I have gained from leading and contributing to over 30 interdisciplinary research projects in aerospace, climate engineering, quantum physics, and artificial intelligence.\r\nAs a Project Manager at NASA-IASC and a research fellow in programs at Cambridge, MIT, and Stanford, I have helped students understand complex concepts like ULF wave analysis, CubeSat AIT systems, and quantum entanglement by breaking them down into storylines and relatable models.  For example, while leading a team for the NASA Space Apps Challenge, I walked participants through data analysis, satellite imaging interpretation, and climate modeling—many of whom had never coded before.  Within 48 hours, we had a global nominee-winning initiative.\r\nYSJs emphasis on scientific leadership and young empowerment is exactly aligned with my mentoring philosophy.  Its organized support and interdisciplinary discourse will help me transform cutting-edge research into practical measures for students.  My goal is to assist young researchers see that every hurdle is an opportunity to expand their knowledge.  With YSJs resources and global network, I hope to inspire them not only to succeed in science, but also to develop a lifetime passion for research and creativity.', 'Hey, Team 123!\r\n I hope you are all doing well.  I saw that your Research Idea Proposal has not yet been submitted, and I wanted to gently remind you that the deadline has passed.\r\n I understand that things can become overwhelming—trust me, I have been there.  But this is a critical stage in your research, and we cannot proceed without it.  If you are lost, confused, or hesitant about your concept, please contact me right away—I am here to help guide you.\r\n Your development as young researchers is important, and any delay is a squandered opportunity to something spectacular.  Let us reset, refocus, and do this within the next 24 hours.  Youve got this, and I am here to help you every step of the way. ', 'As a versatile researcher with a background in aerospace engineering, I have directed and contributed to more than 30 research projects spanning space science, climate engineering, AI-based satellite security, quantum physics, and hybrid propulsion.  My specialties include CubeSat AIT (Assembly, Integration, and Testing), ULF wave analysis, GNSS systems, aerodynamics, and AI applications in space and environmental systems.\r\n One of my most prominent projects is the study of Pc5 ultra-low frequency waves and their diagnostic role in the Earths magnetosphere, which uses INTERMAGNET and Egyptian observatory data during magnetic storms—this work has been presented at global conferences such as AGU Chapman and is being prepared for academic publication.\r\nIn addition, I developed ShieldCam, an AI-powered system, and AD ASTRA, a hybrid propulsion optimization platform for sustainable satellite propulsion.  The NASA Space Apps Challenge acknowledged these apps, and I got the Global Nominee Award.\r\n I have spoken at a number of major conferences, including the major Conference on Aerospace and Mechanics (ICAM 2025), where I studied cryocooler integration in nanosatellite systems.  I have also submitted work on rocket refueling systems and magnetic coil design for ISRS collaborations.\r\nBeyond technical research, I actively mentor kids in research through my responsibilities as Project Manager at NASA-IASC and senior judge at ISEF and IEEE YESIST12, molding the future generation of scientists through advice, workshops, and innovation camps.  My objective is to continue conducting research that connects sustainability and space, while also promoting diversity and STEM access around the world.', 15, '2nd half of July', 'I am one of your alumnae', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-01 15:01:38', NULL, 0, NULL),
(43, 'SYSJ0279', 'Montaser Mostafa', 'abdelmogheethmontaser@gmail.com', '+201008562386', 'Egypt', 'male', '2009-04-14', 'STEM schools ', '11', '3.8', '', 'B+ in biology ', 'This quote resonates with me because I have realized experience-based mentorship in entrepreneurship, business, and science is more than academic knowledge- it is about mentoring, being patient and creative, and encouraging others to take ownership of their own learning. At my STEM high school in Qena, Egypt, I had the opportunity to engage with scientific research and I realized my interests have always been at the intersection of biology, clean energy, and technology. Because of the support from a research institution, I was able to develop and supervise a research project in which, using anaerobic digestion and microbial fuel cells, the organic waste was converted to usable electricity. My project got ed for the Intel ISEF national finals and not only delivered to me a deep knowledge of science, but also provided me with an opportunity to help my peers through a challenge to collaborate on some research. \r\n\r\nLooking back at these collective STEM experiences, I found joy, not only in figuring things out, but in supporting others in their understanding and engagement with science. Whether it was explaining anaerobic respiration and biogas to a group of students, or assisting classmates with building prototypes that actually worked, I learned to simplify complex problems, so I had a way to make things really fun. I often volunteered to', 'I noticed you have yet to submit your research idea proposal and the deadline has passed. I understand that sometimes you can become crowded and overwhelmed with lots of brainstorming and working with others, but deadlines are important in research and being part of a team.\r\nPlease  me ASAP on your progress. If you are hitting road blocks or confused, please let me know and I will help you clarify your next steps. YSJ is all about taking initiative and being accountable, and your team can do that we just need to get them there.\r\nLets work to see a proposal submitted in the next 24 hours. I will support you no problem, just need to see your commitment. You can do this \r\nLooking forward to your response!\r\n— Montaser (YSJ Senior Researcher)', 'As a student in a STEM high school located in Qena, Egypt, I have developed a strong foundation in the research process, especially at the intersection of biology, environmental science, and renewable energy. I focus primarily on biotechnological technologies with sustainable energy applications, as evidenced by a project that converted organic waste into clean electricity. In this project, I used anaerobic digestion to produce methane gas, used biohydrogen production from microalgae, and generated electricity using alkaline fuel cells. I developed and built a functional prototype with IoT-based monitoring systems using sensors and the ESP32 microcontroller. The project was even ed for book tokens for the Intel ISEF (Egypt) local and national rounds and was hailed for its innovative nature and practical impact. \r\nI have also been involved in capstone research related to unconventional methods of energy generation and storage. Working with a partner, we accomplished a goal of producing 0.04 kWh in 5 minutes while utilizing thermoelectric generators and creative energy storage. We were in confined dimensions and material constraints when planning the design too. \r\nThroughout my research process, I have contributed to presentations and scientific posters. One poster was bilingual (English–Arabic) and contained previously unpublished work. I presented it at national STEM exhibitions. Currently, I am involved mentoring other students in designing experiments and analysing data. ', 5, 'N/A', 'Telegram ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-01 19:22:08', NULL, 0, NULL),
(44, 'SYSJ0281', 'Rahma Mahmoud', 'rahmamahmoudahmed986@gmail.com', '01004682503', 'Egypt', 'female', '2008-05-16', 'Minya Al Qamh Secondary SChool for Girls', '12', '95%', 'Biology,Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy,Chemistry,Classics,Computer Science,Data Science,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering),Mathematics,Robotics', 'Biology: 94% in Grade 11           Chemistry: 89% in Grade 11        Math: 96% in Grade 11', 'Mentorship in scientific research goes beyond just understanding theories—it’s about creating a safe space where students feel empowered to ask, explore, and fail forward. I’ve come to appreciate this deeply as a science student who also loves sharing knowledge with others.\r\n\r\nIn school, I’ve always found joy in explaining biology or chemistry to classmates in a way that made them say “Oh, now I get it.” During exam periods, I’d often  mini-study groups where I helped break down complex topics—like enzyme reactions or ecological cycles—into visuals and step-by-step logic. What I learned from those moments is that being a mentor is about listening first, then guiding with empathy.\r\n\r\nYSJ’s vision of nurturing young researchers resonates with me strongly. As someone who hopes to pursue neuroscience or biomedical sciences, I’m fascinated by how mentorship can actually shape scientific curiosity, especially for students who feel intimidated by research. I see YSJ not just as a journal, but as a launchpad for young minds, and I want to contribute by supporting students in finding research questions that truly excite them.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to become part of a research community where I don’t only grow, but also lift others with me. Mentoring younger researchers in YSJ would give me the chance to guide them in building good research habits, staying consistent, and believing in their ideas. I’ve seen that spark in peers before—when they finally solve something hard—and I want to help ignite more of those moments.\r\n\r\nWhether it’s helping a student refine a hypothesis or supporting them through the writing block, I believe I’m ready to meet YSJ’s high standards—not just as a student, but as a mentor who wants others to shine too.', 'Hey Team \r\nI noticed that the research idea proposal deadline passed and we haven’t submitted anything yet. I understand that things can get overwhelming, but we’re at a crucial point right now.\r\n\r\nLets regroup and push through this together — even if the idea isn’t “perfect” yet, we need to have something to build on. Think of this as a first draft, not a final commitment.\r\n\r\nI’m happy to review or brainstorm with you today or tomorrow if that helps. Let’s aim to have a version ready in the next 24 hours — we’ve got this \r\n\r\nPlease  a once you’ve seen this, and let me know how I can support. You’re not alone in this.', 'Although I am still in high school, I have pursued research with deep interest and discipline. My primary areas of focus have been biology, psychology, and environmental science—fields where I enjoy asking “why” and exploring how systems interact.\r\n\r\nI have participated in multiple school-based science projects that followed structured research methods. One of my notable experiences was designing a project on the effect of water pH levels on plant growth, where I d controlled environments and tracked data over several weeks. I learned to use Excel for data analysis and presented my findings to both peers and teachers.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I conducted a literature review on the psychology of memory retention and how it connects to nutrition and sleep quality. I d a report supported by scholarly articles and explained it in a school seminar, which helped me understand the importance of academic writing and citing properly.\r\n\r\nOutside of school, I regularly participate in online science forums, MOOCs, and research competitions that deepen my exposure to research ethics and methods. Though I have not yet published a formal paper, I’m confident in my ability to analyze, write, and contribute meaningfully in collaborative academic settings.\r\n\r\nI’m excited to develop my skills further at YSJ and contribute to high-level student-led research as both a learner and mentor.', 6, 'June:  Weekdays: 4 PM – 8 PM  Weekends: 2 PM – 6 PM  July:  More flexible due to summer break  Available most days: 12 PM – 6 PM  August:  Available daily: 3 PM – 7 PM  September:  School resumes mid-month  Weekdays: 5 PM – 7 PM  Weekends: 1 PM – 5 PM', 'A science competition group on WhatsApp.', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-02 01:14:15', '{\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"6\",\"Chemistry\":\"10\",\"Classics\":\"6\",\"Computer Science\":\"10\",\"Data Science\":\"10\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"10\",\"Mathematics\":\"10\",\"Robotics\":\"10\"}', 0, NULL),
(45, 'SYSJ0114', 'Silina Saher', 'lenasaher320@gmail.com', '01280844929', 'Egypt', 'female', '2009-09-01', 'Sohag stem school', '11', '4.00', '', '', 'Mentorship in scientific research is the art of transforming curiosity into impactful discoveries. Its not merely about understanding theories, but about inspiring others to envision the broader implications and encouraging them to ask, What if?\r\n\r\nMy enthusiasm for research began with interdisciplinary projects that unite biology, AI, and sustainability. I made Eco‑Loop Plus, which s a smart, self-sustaining ecosystem. It uses algae to produce clean energy and purify water, while sensors and AI track air quality and system performance the AI feature helps in anticipating when the system needs to be cleaned, tracking energy production slumps, and even provides tips on how to make adjustments in order to  balance.\r\n\r\nI also worked on BioSynth Skin, a design of an intelligent artificial skin that leverages medical data and synthetic biology to recover more quickly and react to numerous conditions.These experiences have illustrated that research is not linear, highlighting the importance of mentorship. Students will usually start with early failures, questioning their ideas and losing their confidence. My role as a mentor is to reassure them that their questions are valid and assist them in finding solutions.\r\n\r\nAcademically, I am drawn to sustainable biomedical engineering and computational biology. YSJs global network provides an opportunity to challenge my own assumptions, exchange ideas, and be exposed to new research approaches. I would, as a mentor, prefer to assist students to transform unclear thoughts into feasible proposals, watch them excite as they crystallize.\r\n\r\nFor instance, I once helped a struggling colleague with the carbon cycle to understand it in terms that went beyond the diagrams, connecting it with climate change, algae photosynthesis, and energy systems. Another time, a friend was on the verge of abandoning complicated redox reactions until we simplified them step by step to the level where they were teaching someone else. These incidents remind us why mentorship matters: it transforms I cant into \"I did.\"\r\nYSJ\'s vision to empower young researchers is just what my mission—both as a researcher and as an inspirer of generating excitement in others—is all about.\r\n', 'hey team 123\r\n\r\njust remembered we still dont have the research idea proposal done. I understand it is hard to choose just one idea or even be sure that its good enough, but we have to get it over with so we can move on.\r\n\r\nlets work on putting together even a rough outline by the end of the week. it doesn\'t have to be perfect — we can refine it later as a group. if someone is stuck or would prefer to bounce ideas off me, shoot me an message anytime.\r\n\r\nlet\'s get it done.', 'My research experience is couched in my interest in bringing biology, AI, and green solutions together. One of the things that I developed is **Eco‑Loop Plus**, a smart system that uses algae to produce clean energy and clean water. What is new about it is how it brings together sensors and AI to track such as oxygen levels and water quality and then suggests changes to keep the system in good working order.\r\n\r\nI also worked on **BioSynth Skin**, a project for an AI‑assisted artificial skin using synthetic biology and medical data to speed up wound healing and react to environmental changes.\r\n\r\nBesides project work, I enjoy helping others see science as real and enjoyable. For instance, I taught my friend the carbon cycle by connecting it with real environmental challenges we are facing today, so it did not feel abstract. I also taught them step by step how to balance redox reactions, and they could do it on their own by the end.\r\n\r\nMy passion is now to continue to pursue how technology and biology can be applied to solve real problems and to be able to share that interest with younger students. To me, research is not only about finding answers but also about having quality questions and to translate ideas into something that makes a difference.\r\n', 14, 'in 6 , 7,8,9,10,11 july I will travel in ,25 july I have an event', 'a friend', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-02 02:22:46', NULL, 0, NULL),
(46, 'SYSJ0347', 'Hazem Taha', 'hazemmtaha00@gmail.com', '+201270313227', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-04-02', 'Armand Hammer United World College of the American West (UWC-USA)', 'Grade 11', '4.00 (Unweighted)', 'Biology,Gender Studies & Inequality,Sociology & Anthropology', 'Biology: A', 'As a person deeply involved in research, both social and scientific, the quote reflects on how I can turn the difficulties I encountered in research into the goals of my mentorship.\r\n\r\nThe first goal is to build an initial and strong background of the field and its supporting research tools. For instance, many students may not have the knowledge that they can propose an experiment and write expected results instead of just doing review articles, and others mistakenly think that a review article is just a display of current and previous research, not a way to draw further conclusions and encourage future research. In social sciences and gender studies, they may not know the basics they need for empirical research, like how to prepare and extract manuscripts from an interview, how to manipulate quantitative data using SPSS, the same for qualitative data using NVIVO, and finally draw non-biased conclusions. Such knowledge will help them choose a more successful approach to their research inquiries.\r\n\r\nThe second goal is to give scholars/junior researchers their space to decide. The decision of which methodology, research questions, or even tools to use should be authentic and only based on what the junior researchers want. As my goal is to only supervise, I may not intervene in their research process.\r\n\r\nFinally, my third goal is to help them leverage every single source they can. In my previous research programs, some had mentoring faculty feedback, and others had writing centers. I’m not sure what resources YSJ has, but I will do my best to make my scholars make the most out of them.', 'Good evening/morning to you all,\r\n\r\nI noticed that your team did not submit the research proposal. Can you inform me of any obstacles you are currently facing or hardships? Finally, please submit as soon as possible and stick to the upcoming tasks for a better evaluation, which I have been expecting for such wonderful junior researchers like you!\r\n\r\nBest,\r\nHazem\r\n', 'I have been involved in research in various fields and research programs.\r\n\r\nIn biology, I have had 3 research experiences, starting with a minimal school task on nutrition in STEM schools. My team and I were able to assess the nutritional qualities and energy in the daily servings versus an average basal metabolic rate  (BMR) and what an average high school student needs (attached). Then, I joined YSJ and conducted research (with Ali, B.) on how ADHD symptom severity could be related to malnutrition and/or school days (attached in the next page). I then joined Pioneer Academics with mentoring faculty Dr. David Veselik. I am currently preparing an experiment proposal on using allogeneic chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T cells by a CRISPR Cas-CLOVER system to kill HIV-infected cells after reversing latency. I have finished a first draft of the introduction and literature review (https://docs.google.com/document/d/1_o-BeYvcCnIdNoOEO21bTj1jGmIsNFa8/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=110838578479928036253&rtpof=true&sd=true).\r\n\r\nIn gender and social studies, I had two research experiences. It started with Lumiere Education Individual Research Program with mentoring faculty Dr. Jaleah Rutledge and Dr. Teju Limbu. I finished a literature review paper on how menstruation is typically gendered, the hardships cis women and trans men face in the workplace because of menstruation,  perspective of trans women on menstruation, and recommendations (https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hfwp0mN_2eDfWdvXG9pFn0R7VNNWNjc3/view?usp=sharing). I then joined Daftar Ahwal Data research and management program, and built a quantitative archive on the incidents of violence in Egyptian schools and correlated it with gendered patterns in the report (https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1MitW1ZqY1CzvFA5pwJIX9xKKkMSUt7dj?usp=sharing). \r\n\r\n** Note: the portal is only accepting one file. Thus, the mistakes of A Comparative Study of the Perceived Stress Levels and Sources of Stress are highlighted in the following document: https://docs.google.com/document/d/11mzvn6QT8YAtVVPIoB4IpjqbwdRQQxXg/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=110838578479928036253&rtpof=true&sd=true **', 10, 'Nothing significant', 'I was a junior researcher', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-03 00:33:53', '{\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Gender Studies & Inequality\":\"7\",\"Sociology & Anthropology\":\"5\"}', 0, 'Biology');
