you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science.', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science.Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science.', 18, 'N/A', 'FAcebook', NULL, NULL, 'under_review', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-03 20:32:03', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"5\"}', 1, NULL),
(54, 'SYSJ0368', 'vhbjnm', 'اتنتم', 'رالاىةو', 'رىلاة', 'female', '2008-03-09', 'Red Sea ', 'طك', 'ك', 'Aerospace Engineering,Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy', 'التانتمنك', 'AFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania have partnered to  an engaging online\r\nprogram that invites you to explore cultural differences, practice\r\nsocial innovation, learn about sustainability, and take action in your\r\ncommunity!\r\nLet’s look at what you will accomplish during these next 12\r\nweeks.\r\n● You will enhance your personal growth and self-awareness by\r\nreflecting on your own community and culture, as well as the\r\ncultures of your peers from around the world.\r\n● With this foundation, you will then take a deep dive into social\r\ninnovation terms, theory and approaches, cultivate\r\nself-awareness for impact, and adopt the role of an observer in\r\nyour community.\r\n● Finally, while considering sustainability and the impact of\r\nclimate change, you will discover, design and develop a social\r\ninnovation project.\r\nWhat does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means\r\nAFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania have partnered to  an engaging online\r\nprogram that invites you to explore cultural differences, practice\r\nsocial innovation, learn about sustainability, and take action in your\r\ncommunity!\r\nLet’s look at what you will accomplish during these next 12\r\nweeks.\r\n● You will enhance your personal growth and self-awareness by\r\nreflecting on your own community and culture, as well as the\r\ncultures of your peers from around the world.\r\n● With this foundation, you will then take a deep dive into social\r\ninnovation terms, theory and approaches, cultivate\r\nself-awareness for impact, and adopt the role of an observer in\r\nyour community.\r\n● Finally, while considering sustainability and the impact of\r\nclimate change, you will discover, design and develop a social\r\ninnovation project.\r\nWhat does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means', 'AFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania have partnered to  an engaging online\r\nprogram that invites you to explore cultural differences, practice\r\nsocial innovation, learn about sustainability, and take action in your\r\ncommunity!\r\nLet’s look at what you will accomplish during these next 12\r\nweeks.\r\n● You will enhance your personal growth and self-awareness by\r\nreflecting on your own community and culture, as well as the\r\ncultures of your peers from around the world.\r\n● With this foundation, you will then take a deep dive into social\r\ninnovation terms, theory and approaches, cultivate\r\nself-awareness for impact, and adopt the role of an observer in\r\nyour community.\r\n● Finally, while considering sustainability and the impact of\r\nclimate change, you will discover, design and develop a social\r\ninnovation project.\r\nWhat does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means\r\nAFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania have partnered to  an engaging online\r\nprogram that invites you to explore cultural differences, practice\r\nsocial innovation, learn about sustainability, and take action in your\r\ncommunity!\r\nLet’s look at what you will accomplish during these next 12\r\nweeks.\r\n● You will enhance your personal growth and self-awareness by\r\nreflecting on your own community and culture, as well as the\r\ncultures of your peers from around the world.\r\n● With this foundation, you will then take a deep dive into social\r\ninnovation terms, theory and approaches, cultivate\r\nself-awareness for impact, and adopt the role of an observer in\r\nyour community.\r\n● Finally, while considering sustainability and the impact of\r\nclimate change, you will discover, design and develop a social\r\ninnovation project.\r\nWhat does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means', 'What does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means you will  a prototype of intervention in your\r\ncommunity. Once you have this prototype, you will then test it out\r\nwithin your community and get feedback on how it can be\r\nimproved. Finally, you’ll present your project plans through a 3-5\r\nminute presentation. By the end of this course, you will receive the\r\nAdvanced Certificate on Global Citizenship for Social Impact from\r\nAFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania.\r\nWe are so excited to start this journey with you, and invite you\r\nto embark with courage and curiosity What does this mean exactly?\r\nIt means you will  a prototype of intervention in your\r\ncommunity. Once you have this prototype, you will then test it out\r\nwithin your community and get feedback on how it can be\r\nimproved. Finally, you’ll present your project plans through a 3-5\r\nminute presentation. By the end of this course, you will receive the\r\nAdvanced Certificate on Global Citizenship for Social Impact from\r\nAFS and the Center for Social Impact Strategy at the University of\r\nPennsylvania.\r\nWe are so excited to start this journey with you, and invite you\r\nto embark with courage and curiosity▶ Put your intercultural skills to use by respecting diversity! The\r\nforum is a brave space for people of all races, genders, sexes, ages,\r\nsexual orientations, religions, disabilities and socioeconomic\r\nstatuses. This is an opportunity to learn about and listen to\r\nindividuals’ unique perspectives. Offensive language, jokes, and\r\ncomments targeted to individuals’ social categories and identities\r\nwill not be tolerated.\r\n▶ Activity participate! Take responsibility for your own learning.\r\nParticipate in the activities and forums. Learn from your fellow\r\nChangemakers, read their comments and ask them questions!\r\nPractice ow more about. Stay curious!\r\n▶ Try to demonstrat', 79, 'كمات', 'بلالاتى', NULL, NULL, 'under_review', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-03 20:43:19', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"5\",\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"5\"}', 1, NULL),
(55, 'SYSJ0137', 'Sohibe Mohamed', 'sohibebehairy@gmail.com', '01014530203', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-10-06', 'STEM Obour', '11', '3.89/4.0', 'Biology,Computer Science,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering),Mathematics,Robotics', 'Mathematics: A, Biology: A, Computer Science: B+', 'I believe that I have helped my community for several times for example,\r\n\r\nI always help my friends in studying, especially in Biology. I have helped them in class, and in the final exam period. Mainly because I know many topics and concepts that I studied in depth from test books. In addition, I have prepared a presentation that discusses our practical exam with a brief summary, animations, and attractive pictures, and they loved it. As a result, they were confident in the exam, because they studied from it, also some of them began considering in biology after seeing how many interesting topics are found in the world of Biology.\r\n\r\nI have also helped my friends in class during the Computer Science session. Furthermore, I have a great background in programming languages, especially Python. Occasionally, my teacher lets me prepare presentations and scripts, to showcase it in class, and teach them from it. Correspondingly, they loved it, and some of them were obsessed with learning Python.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I have conducted a research idea and showcased it to a foreign committee from FAU (Florida Atlantic University). It was about treating a disease called Retinitis Pigmentosa by using STEM cells injection therapy. Moreover, my team and I made a presentation, that explains the research idea in depth. In conclusion, they admired the idea so much, and some of them believed that we might have a chance with this idea. \r\n\r\nTo sum up, I always assist anyone who needs my help, as I always use my knowledge to benefit the community.\r\n', 'Dear team 123, \r\nI know how it feels to submit a task under pressure and in short time. Believe me, I have been in the same situation multiple times. Also, I recognize that you might be sad or think that you are not taking any steps further, but here is my advice. Giving up is not an option here at YSJ, rather you must continue suffering, and keep pushing forward till you reach your goal. You must know that you are a unique person with many distinct abilities, and believe me when you submit the task, you will notice how much you have enhanced than before. Additionally, I am here if you need any help, I will try my best to support you any time. Now go and show me what you got in yourself, I have faith that you are going to make an amazing research paper, but try not to overtake mine :)\r\nBest regards, \r\nSohibe Mohamed', 'Initially, I have not made any research paper yet, but I am currently learning more about it (layout, academic writing, citation), as I am hoping to publish my first one this holiday. Instead, I have researched various things for example,\r\n\r\nCapstone, in my capstone project (school project), which was about substituting non-renewable energy with green energy (renewable), I have researched hundreds of things including Egypt grand challenges (urban congestion, overpopulation, climatic change, etc...), green suitable energy methods (PHS, Solar chimney, and solar PVs), and prior projects (Aswan high dam, Niagara falls, and Three georges dam).\r\n\r\nI have also conducted a research for the biology club, which was about treating Retinitis Pigmentosa by using STEM cells injection therapy, and showcased it by a presentation to a foreign committee.\r\n\r\nCurrently, I am researching for science fairs project ideas. Furthermore, I am researching critical global problems including, Brain rot, and Climatic change, hoping to develop a suitable solution (project) to treat it.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, I have researched many times, but have not yet conducted any research paper, that is why I am hoping that YSJ will assist me with that, as I am optimistic that it will have a significant impact on my life. \r\n', 8, 'I do not have any right now', 'Google search', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 01:47:56', '{\"Biology\":\"9\",\"Computer Science\":\"9\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"9\",\"Mathematics\":\"8\",\"Robotics\":\"6\"}', 0, NULL);
INSERT INTO `applications` (`id`, `user_id`, `full_name`, `email`, `contact_number`, `country`, `gender`, `birth_date`, `institution`, `grade_year`, `gpa`, `interest`, `grade_previous`, `first_essay`, `second_essay`, `third_essay`, `hours_commitment`, `time_blocks`, `hear_about`, `commented_file_path`, `cv_path`, `status`, `assigned_to`, `reviewer_suggestion`, `personal_qualifications`, `research_skills`, `analytic_skills`, `mentorship_skills`, `academic_writing`, `academic_performance`, `commitments`, `total_score`, `overall_rating`, `notes`, `submitted_at`, `interest_ratings`, `is_deleted`, `accepted_field`) VALUES
(56, 'SYSJ066', 'Marlowe Samuel', 'marlowsamuel140@gmail.com', '011111436916', 'egypt', 'male', '2008-04-19', 'Grade 10 ', 'year 10', '3.9', 'Computer Science', '94% in grade 10 in thanwya amma program', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties.”\r\n\r\nThis quote reflects the dual responsibility of any mentor: clarity in thought and compassion in leadership. As a student researcher, I’ve gained both through my experiences in programs like Lumiere and Pioneer Academics, where I explored topics from neurocomputing and connectomics to green hydrogen and environmental sustainability. These programs taught me how to break down complex ideas, ask the right questions, and remain patient through scientific uncertainty.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to pursue interdisciplinary research combining neuroscience, AI, and sustainability. As a mentor, I aim to help students transform broad interests into clear, researchable questions and build confidence in their scientific voices. I especially want to support students who, like me, may come from underrepresented regions or lack access to elite research networks. YSJ’s mission to empower young global scientists deeply aligns with this vision.\r\n\r\nAt YSJ, I hope to guide young researchers in formulating hypotheses, analyzing data, and refining their writing—while also encouraging resilience and creativity. My past mentoring experiences include helping a student frame a project on plastic degradation using PETase enzymes and supporting peers with neuroscience writing, including simplifying memory circuits and emotion regulation pathways. Seeing their excitement grow was a reminder that mentorship isn’t just about instruction—it’s about belief.\r\n\r\nYSJ provides a unique platform to combine high academic standards with peer mentorship. Its collaborative structure, interdisciplinary openness, and student leadership culture are exactly what I value. I’m ready to contribute meaningfully, learn from others, and inspire students to realize they have something original to offer the world of science.\r\n', 'Hey Team 123! \r\n\r\nI noticed that the Research Idea Proposal deadline has passed, and we haven’t received your submission yet. I completely understand that things can get overwhelming—especially when balancing research with school and other commitments—but it’s really important that we stay on track to make the most of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nYour proposal doesn’t need to be perfect at this stage—we’re here to refine and support you along the way! The key thing is to submit a clear draft of your topic idea, research question, and any initial plan so we can move forward and give feedback.\r\n\r\nPlease aim to submit it within the next 48 hours. If there’s any blocker, confusion, or if you need help finalizing your idea, I’m just a message away. I believe in your potential, and I’m here to support you. Let’s get this done so we can dive into the exciting part—building your research! \r\n\r\nLooking forward to your  soon!', 'My research background is rooted in interdisciplinary scientific inquiry, particularly at the intersection of neuroscience, artificial intelligence, and environmental sustainability. I am currently a student researcher in two highly ive programs: the Lumiere Education Individual Research Scholar Program and the Pioneer Academics Program, where I’ve had the opportunity to work closely with university-level mentors.\r\n\r\nThrough Lumiere, I’ve conducted research exploring the role of epigenetics in mental health, focusing on how environmental factors influence gene expression related to psychological disorders and addiction. This work involved extensive literature synthesis and analysis of recent studies on DNA methylation and histone modifications.\r\n\r\nIn the Pioneer Academics program, I am conducting research under the guidance of Dr. David Gatchell, Director of the MaDE program at Northwestern University. My current project investigates neuroengineering and computational modeling, focusing on brain–computer interfaces and the connectome. This experience has deepened my skills in experimental design, academic writing, and presenting technically complex ideas in accessible ways.\r\n\r\nBeyond these formal programs, I’ve pursued independent studies in environmental science—specifically the potential of green hydrogen and plastic biodegradation—and contributed to community-level science mentorship initiatives. I’ve also participated in STEM competitions such as IEEE YESIST12, where my team developed a sustainable technology concept to tackle waste management.\r\n\r\nWhile I am in the early stages of publishing my first paper, I have presented research and reviewed peers’ work across several student platforms and competitions. I aim to publish in student-led journals and eventually contribute to interdisciplinary journals bridging neuroscience, AI, and sustainability.\r\n\r\nMy research journey has not only developed my academic skills but has also taught me the value of scientific mentorship, which I now hope to extend to others through YSJ.', 6, 'during afternoon', 'friend in MIT now', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-04 17:42:12', '{\"Computer Science\":\"7\"}', 0, NULL),
(57, 'SYSJ078', 'Maya M. Fahmy', 'mayamahmoud918@gmail.com', '01010140113', 'Egypt', 'female', '2009-07-12', 'Saad Zaghloul Distinguished Governmental Language School', '10', '3.916 (97.9%)', 'Computer Science', 'N/A', 'During my time as a junior researcher in previous research programs, I realized that my professors played a crucial role in helping me complete my research papers academically and personally, and that was inspiring enough to decide to be like them. As the written quote shows, it motivates and directs students through difficulties, but it isnt only in difficulties, as the research process is divided into two paths: The first path is when the researcher is confused about the topic and if it fits its goals or not. The second path is the easier one: after determining the methodology and results sections, its the paper structure, which doesn\'t need mentorship as it was needed in the first path, but it mainly focuses on the researcher\'s efforts and readings. For my previous experiences, I worked on a research paper focusing on computer science via music algorithms with my professor, Dr. Sang Won Lee, during my time at Virginia Tech Institute, and currently I am a Computer Science Pioneer research scholar working on machine learning algorithms and cyber threat detection with an applied mathematics research concentration in the Talaria Research Summer Program. For my academic and mentoring goals while at YSJ, I would like to apply the knowledge, ethics, and experiences I gained from my previous research experiences to other researchers to help them not only focus on computer science basics but also develop strong research skills that will benefit them in any field they pursue. This is something I learned from my professors, who were dedicated to shaping me as a real researcher—not a student who copies information from online sources, but one who understands concepts of research as the first priority. In terms of supporting others in science, I have mentored over 100 blind students in scientific writing, mathematics, and science to enable them to participate in their scientific competitions and start their own research proposals.', 'Dear Team 123,\r\n\r\nI would like to remind you that your research proposal deadline task has passed. No one has reached me out if they consider any challenges and I can offer you the ability to extend your deadline. For this, please each one of you contacted me privately about the challenges you faced that made you wouldnt able to finish your task whether personal or academic, I will be happy and appreciate your time to know. Moreover, a message for all of you whatever the challenges you faced, please be appreciated for my time as your mentor and also for your goals as a researcher and I will consider that in your reviews file.\r\n\r\nThank you for your consideration. Waiting for your responses.\r\n\r\nBest,\r\nYour Mentor', 'For my research background in Computer Science, I have started my research journey since my acceptance at TechGirls program to study Computer Science via Music Algorithms under the supervision of Dr. Sang Won Lee which will be published by the beginning of 2026. As by the end of December 2024, I became a CS Pioneer research scholar with a cybersecurity and education research concentrations and my research topic mainly focuses on ML algorithms, cybersecurity and politics. Moreover, I am a Talaria research scholar with applied mathematics research concentration and how it is connected to neuroscience. However, my general research background has started since the seventh grade with my first research paper about Sustainable Biofuel Production from Microalgae Grown in Wastewater, then I worked on a research project related to sustainable composites from date palm fibers and sugar can for a more sustainable environment. In addition to my previous ISEF project that has focused on using ML algorithms for assisting the blind by a prediction system for them. ', 21, 'Pioneer (Dec–Jul), UWC (Jun 29–Jul 11), Talaria (Jun 30–Aug 20), COP30 (Mar–Sep, weekly), CCC (Jul–), YYAS (Jul 17–22), SPINWIP (Jul 7–25)', 'Social Media (Facebook)', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 18:16:31', '{\"Computer Science\":\"9\"}', 0, 'Computer Science'),
(58, 'SYSJ0116', 'Ahmed Nasser', 'ahmednasserdesouky@gmail.com', '01014600921', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-04-21', 'STEM High School for Boys-6 of October ', 'G12', '4.00', '', 'Biology : A', 'Mentorship in research is not only about the knowledge of the science but also about the knowledge of people. I’ve been in situations where classmates appeared to be stuck or unable to decide how to further their ideas. One student could not organize or connect his project data with his hypothesis. I didn’t just tell him what to do I sat with him and initiated the right questions he needed to answer, and that allowed him to develop clarity from his confusion. Watching him strengthen in confidence was the moment when I realized just how much I appreciate guiding others.\r\n\r\nI’ll still aim to pursue biology and medical research, but I intend to also aid others along the way, especially if they are students with a passion but lack direction. I’ve seen how difficult it is when someone feels lost, even when they deeply care about science. Mentorship, to me, is not a title—it’s a responsibility to stand beside someone while they learn how to stand for themselves.\r\n\r\nYSJ’s commitment to leadership, responsibility, and high expectations aligns with what I need to develop into a mentor that leads by example and not by force. I ultimately want to help others move beyond fear and take their frustration and fuel their curiosity in the same way I learned to recharge my own.', 'Hello Team 123,\r\nAs I continue to assess the deadlines, Ive noticed that your proposal of the research idea seems to be absent.\r\n\r\nIm not saying this lightly — its not about missing a deadline. Its about demonstrating you respect the process and the potential of your work. You were ed because we wanted to believe you can think critically and act responsibly — not just when it’s easy, but when it feels that it’s uncomfortable, messy, or overwhelming.\r\n\r\n\r\nResearch is more than a result — its a practice, responsibility, and accountability, including follow-through. Right now, silence and inertia are communicating more than any words could convey. I know each of you can overcome this barrier. But now is the time to demonstrate it.\r\n\r\nSo, heres what I need you to return, within the next 24 hours - a draft. It doesnt even need to be good. It just needs to be real. We can craft together, but we need to have something to weave into an idea and shape.\r\n\r\nThis is your opportunity to step off. Im here, but Im not doing the work for you.\r\nTime to move. \r\nAhmed Nasser Desouky\r\nYSJ Senior Researcher', 'My research background is based on curiosity-driven exploration, specifically in the topics of biology and health sciences. I have pursued research independently through personal projects, summer programs, and competitions. One of my first investigations was on insulin-producing, genetically modified bacteria, which I wrote an essay on to submit for recognition my essay was recognized and awarded a 1000 euro merit-based award from Immerse Education. This project strengthened my knowledge base of molecular biology, biotechnology, and the ethical considerations of synthetic biology. \r\n\r\nSimultaneously, I have developed several projects aimed at resolving environmental issues, such as water pollution and scarcity, air pollution, and renewable energy. Many of these interdisciplinary projects merged environmental science, microbiology, and electrochemistry. Through introductory and intermediate biology, I have been able to design, develop, and evaluate these projects with hand-on experience in scientific method, risk avoidance, and development of safety documentation. \r\n\r\nTo end, I have also competed in the future innovation community, where I was awarded 25% merit-based award for my submission about awareness toward research and how fastly it will enhance scientific, social, and industrial development exponentially. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, there are many other projects, like the dental carriers piece, which has been published in my school biology club website, or the energy balance and metabolic pathways based on a human body.', 8, 'Just G12 study.', 'My school', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-04 20:18:22', '{\"Biology\":\"9\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"5\"}', 0, 'Biology'),
(59, 'SYSJ0282', 'Emad Sameh Emad gerges saad', 'emadsameh2008@gmail.com', '(+20)01271904877', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-03-16', 'Lieutenant General Saad El Shazly Language', '11', '3.6', 'Biology,Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy,Chemistry,Computer Science,Environmental Science,Mathematics,Neuroscience & Neurobiology', 'biology : A+      Chemistry : A+', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties.”\r\n\r\nThis quote reflects how I’ve approached teaching and mentorship. It’s not just about explaining ideas—it’s about being there when someone gets stuck, encouraging them when they doubt themselves, and celebrating their progress, no matter how small. Through founding and leading Path 2 Code, I’ve learned that mentorship is just as much about people as it is about knowledge.\r\n\r\nIn Path 2 Code, I teach C++ to beginners through free Zoom sessions and a YouTube channel. I also developed an app that includes lessons and exercises to support learning. Many of my students have no prior experience with programming, so I focus on making things clear and relatable. When someone doesn’t understand a concept, I try different approaches until it clicks. I’ve learned that the best way to help someone grow is to give them space to ask questions, make mistakes, and find their own path through the problem.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to explore how science can solve real-life problems, especially in areas like environmental research, public health, and technology. I’ve worked on a research project to reduce CO₂ emissions from factories and participated in several competitions like the NASA Hackathon, Climate Science Olympiad, and Purple Comet. These experiences helped me understand how research works, from asking questions to interpreting data, and they’ve shaped how I teach others.\r\n\r\nOne of my favorite moments as a mentor was helping a student who was struggling with recursive functions in C++. He felt lost and ready to quit, but I sat with him, broke the problem into smaller parts, and guided him step by step. When he finally understood it, his confidence changed completely. That’s the impact I want to keep making.\r\n\r\nYSJ’s values match my own. I want to help younger students feel excited about science and show them that research isn’t just for “smart” people—it’s for anyone willing to learn and explore. I believe that, through YSJ, I can continue growing as a mentor and help others discover the scientist in themselves.', 'Just a reminder that your research idea proposal was due recently, and I havent seen it submitted yet. Please make sure to share your idea within the next 24 to 48 hours so we can stay on schedule.\r\nIf you re facing any challenges or need support, feel free to reach out. Im here to help.\r\nLooking forward to your  ', 'Over the past few years, I have taken part in several research projects focused on sustainability and technology. As a member of the Green Aura Team, I worked on a project that explored how to reduce carbon dioxide emissions from factories. We studied industrial processes and looked for innovative ways to cut down pollution. I helped collect data, analyze solutions, and communicate our findings clearly to others.\r\n\r\nI also contributed to a community project that aimed to share environmental opportunities with young people in my area. We encouraged students to take part in climate-related activities and raised awareness about environmental issues through small campaigns and research-based events.\r\n\r\nIn addition to that, I have led an independent educational project called Path 2 Code. Through it, I teach computer programming to beginners using simple lessons, free Zoom sessions, and a mobile app I helped develop. While it was not a typical research paper, I had to learn how students understand coding concepts, test methods of teaching, and improve the content based on feedback.\r\n\r\nThese experiences gave me strong research, communication, and leadership skills. Even though I do not have formal publications yet, I am proud of how I have used research and problem-solving to help others learn and to explore solutions for real-world problems.', 21, 'June 15 – July 15: Running and managing the “Path 2 Code” summer programming course (online classes and student support).     August (Flexible): Preparing for upcoming competitions like ICSC and Climate Science Olympiad (no fixed dates, mostly self-paced).', 'social media', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-04 22:36:22', '{\"Biology\":\"9\",\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"8\",\"Chemistry\":\"8\",\"Computer Science\":\"9\",\"Environmental Science\":\"7\",\"Mathematics\":\"10\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"9\"}', 0, NULL),
(60, 'SYSJ0323', 'Bassant Muhammad ', 'bvssvntmohamed@gmail.com', '01115039193', 'Egypt ', 'female', '2008-08-18', 'Al Saieda Khadija secondary school for girls ', '11', '96.2', '', '56/60', 'Mentorship in scientific research is not only about mastering the content, but about being able to communicate it in a simple way and provide emotional support when students feel stuck or overwhelmed. Through my work on multiple projects, including the geopolymer cement project at ISEF and others at EISTF, I gained valuable experience in simplifying complex concepts and dealing with coordination and experimental challenges.\r\nI also served as a leader in Resala STEM, a volunteer initiative that supports students in the field of science. I was responsible for guiding the team during our field visits and was always committed to supporting them emotionally, scientifically, and practically. That experience taught me how to truly listen, understand each member’s perspective, and help them move forward without pressure.\r\nMy academic goal is to continue in scientific research particularly in space sciences and to integrate this passion with mentoring the next generation of young researchers. I want to be a role model for those around me, encouraging them to discover their true capabilities.\r\nWhat I admire about YSJ is that it offers an inspiring environment for growth, bringing together people who are genuinely passionate about science. This will help me enhance my mentoring skills while contributing to a community that supports real, meaningful development.', ' Good evening Team 123,\r\nI want to start by saying that I genuinely appreciate your efforts, and I believe in your potential. That said, my role as a mentor is to help you grow not just in knowledge, but in responsibility, professionalism, and time management.\r\n\r\nMissing the Research Proposal deadline is not just a small delay it affects the timeline of the whole team and reflects on our collective commitment. That’s something we need to address immediately.\r\n\r\nIf youre facing any difficulties unclear ideas, confusion, or even lack of direction that’s perfectly normal. But it’s important that you reach out, ask for help, and communicate openly. Scientific research is built on accountability and honest collaboration.\r\n\r\nI’m asking you to submit the proposal within the next 24 hours. If there’s anything holding you back, please message me directly and we’ll find a solution together.\r\n\r\nI’m not here to pressure you, but to prepare you to become responsible, capable researchers who respect the value of every step in this process.\r\nI’m looking forward to your submission. I know you can do this and I’m here to support you, every step of the way.', 'Over the past few years, I have participated in various research and leadership projects that significantly shaped my academic and professional journey. I served as the principal investigator in the Geopolymer Cement project, which was showcased at ISEF, where I was responsible for laboratory experiments, data analysis, and guiding the team’s scientific direction toward sustainability and eco-friendly materials.\r\nI also developed an innovative wearable device (a smart jacket) that generates electricity from body heat, integrates AI for health data analysis, and utilizes blockchain for data security. This interdisciplinary project is designed for future submission to platforms like NASA challenges or ISEF, blending biothermal energy, AI, and biomedical monitoring.\r\nAdditionally, I authored a scientific literature-based neuroscience article for the IYNA Journal, addressing a novel topic in an academically rigorous format.\r\nAs a team leader in Resala STEM, I supported members emotionally, scientifically, and logistically during volunteering fieldwork, learning how to simplify complex concepts and manage group dynamics.\r\nI was also ed for competitive research-oriented programs such as Medical Awareness, Tomorrow’s Female Innovators (TFI), and the NIS Research Program, where I deepened my understanding of research methodology, mentorship, and academic writing.\r\nThrough these experiences, I have developed a strong foundation in scientific inquiry, teamwork, and mentoring preparing me to contribute meaningfully to YSJ’s rigorous and dynamic research environment.', 7, 'Between June and September, I will be participating in a few academic and volunteering activities. I am actively involved with Resala STEM as a volunteer and mentor, and I am also taking part in science competitions such as ISEF and the NASA Hackathon. Additionally, I may join a few other research-related events or hackathons during this period.  However, I am confident in my ability to manage my time effectively, and I am fully committed to prioritizing my responsibilities at YSJ. I will make sure that any other activities do not interfere with my role and duties as a senior researcher.', 'Whatsapp ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 01:24:12', NULL, 0, NULL),
(61, 'SYSJ0391', 'Ahmed Saif Eldeen', 'ahmedsaifeldeen1314@gmail.com', '+201091310012', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-08-13', 'STEM', 'adsaf', '8', 'Architecture', '5', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. ', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. ', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science. ', 52, 'lklj', 'jklj', NULL, NULL, 'under_review', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 21:00:21', '{\"Architecture\":\"10\"}', 1, NULL),
(62, 'SYSJ0263', 'Pradipti Nath', 'pradiptinath@gmail.com', '9833896847', 'India', 'female', '2009-01-11', 'Oberoi International School', '11', '3.8', 'Biology,Economics,Environmental Science', 'Biology IGCSE Level - A* (96%), Economics IGCSE (87%) and IB Diploma HL, Business Strategy (Self Taught via Coursera, Springpod), Environmental Science (IB Diploma at a Higher Level). ', 'To me, mentorship in scientific research isn’t just about answering questions it’s about equipping learners to ask the right ones. It requires patience, clarity, and the humility to guide rather than instruct. Through my own academic journey, I’ve learned that the most meaningful mentorship happens not in delivering solutions, but in walking beside others as they discover them for themselves. It’s with this mindset that I believe I align with the ethos of the Young Scientists Journal (YSJ). Over the past year, I’ve led a club of 50+ students where we explored Artificial Intelligence and its real-world applications. These weren’t just lectures they were labs of curiosity, where we demystified neural networks and debated the ethics of facial recognition. I vividly recall one student struggling with machine learning algorithms. Instead of simplifying the concept for her, I challenged her to reverse-engineer a model using real data. The moment she cracked it and presented her findings to the club was a defining one for both of us. \r\nOutside screen-lit classrooms, I initiated a study group for IGCSE Biology students, held weekly at a nearby garden. What began as casual tutoring evolved into a space of open dialogue. We’d relate mitosis to leaf patterns around us, turning the natural world into a live textbook! One student, previously demotivated by rigid academic structures and began to show up early bringing questions! Perhaps the most formative experience was leading a team of six students on a collaborative research paper titled Citizen Science: How People Use Digital Tools to Share Local Data. As the team lead, I steered us through academic writing, methodological frameworks, and late-night debates over ethical data collection. It wasn’t just distributing tasks but about learning how to hold space for uncertainty, disagreement, and eventual insight. \r\nMy academic and mentoring goals center on making research feel personal and purposeful and I hope to do the same at YSJ too. \r\n', 'Hey Team123!\r\nI noticed the Research Idea Proposal deadline has passed, and we haven’t received your submission yet. I completely understand that things can get hectic, but it’s really important we stay on track to ensure the entire research cycle runs smoothly.\r\nIf youre facing any challenges be it finalizing your idea, team coordination, or anything else, please don’t hesitate to reach out. I’d be happy to help you troubleshoot or guide you through the next steps!  That said, I’ll need your finalized proposal within the next 48 hours so we can move forward without delays. Let’s push through this milestone, you’ve got this!\r\n', 'My research background spans both independent work and collaborative projects, rooted in social impact and real-world relevance.\r\nThrough the Young Researchers for Social Impact (YRSI) program by YLAC, I was ed as one of 90 students from over 19,000 applicants. Our cohort explored the theme of digital citizen science, specifically how individuals and local communities use digital tools to collect, share, and analyze local data for environmental and social change. I co-authored a research paper with six peers, where I served as the team lead. We investigated case studies, digital platforms, and ethical concerns around data collection. I guided the group through task delegation, research design, and synthesis of findings into a well-structured final paper. This experience helped me grow as a collaborative researcher and gave me a deeper appreciation for grassroots participation in scientific inquiry.\r\nSeparately, I worked on a Global Perspectives project at school with three peers on Gender Inequality in India. We explored the issue through educational access, wage disparity, and cultural norms. Our research combined interviews, survey design, and secondary data, and culminated in a multimedia presentation and report. I took the lead on data interpretation, using visual analysis tools to highlight gaps in opportunity for women across urban and rural India. This project taught me the value of contextualizing data within lived experiences and emphasized the role of narrative in research communication...', 14, 'Aug and September.  Mid July', 'Reddit', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 05:44:56', '{\"Biology\":\"8\",\"Economics\":\"9\",\"Environmental Science\":\"7\"}', 0, 'Economics'),
(63, 'SYSJ0139', 'Rawan Mohammed Abdel Mohsen Mohammed Mohamed Shaheen  ', 'rawan.mhd89@gmail.com', '01588830023', 'Egypt', 'female', '2008-01-27', 'school Giza Secondary ', 'Third secondary grade ', '90 percent ', '', 'I studied art for 12 years, scientific research for 2 years, space and other subjects, and computers for 3 years.', 'The quote emphasizes the dual nature of scientific mentorship: deep understanding of concepts and the emotional intelligence to guide students through challenges. My journey in scientific research has shaped me to meet these expectations. With hands-on experience in biotechnology and environmental science projects—some of which were presented at national science fairs—I’ve gained both technical depth and a practical mindset that helps students navigate complex scientific problems.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to contribute meaningfully to research in sustainable technologies while fostering a community of empowered young researchers. As a mentor, I aim to simplify complex theories, cultivate curiosity, and help students turn their ideas into meaningful solutions. Programs like YSJ offer access to an interdisciplinary network, feedback-rich environments, and global perspectives that would strengthen my guidance skills and widen the horizons of the mentees I support.\r\n\r\nOne instance that reflects my mentoring ability occurred when I guided a team of high school students struggling with hypothesis formulation for their microbiology project. By breaking down their confusion into small, clear questions and encouraging them to connect the topic to real-world issues, they eventually developed a compelling, testable research question—and won third place in their regional competition. Watching them grow more confident reminded me why mentorship is so impactful: it transforms uncertainty into passion.', 'Hey Team 123! \r\nI noticed your proposal hasn’t been submitted yet. Just a friendly reminder that deadlines are essential not only for keeping the program on track but also for helping you move forward with clarity and purpose.\r\n\r\nIf youre facing any challenges—technical, personal, or brainstorming-related—please don’t hesitate to reach out. I’m here to support you. Let’s try to submit it by the end of the day, even if its a rough draft. Progress over perfection \r\n\r\nYou’ve got this. Can’t wait to see what you’ve been working on! \r\n', 'My research background spans both environmental innovation and psychological health. I have led and participated in research initiatives that aim to develop sustainable, science-based solutions to pressing global issues. One of my primary research contributions includes working on a device that captures carbon dioxide from the air and transforms it into organic fertilizer. This ongoing project combines environmental engineering with practical climate action, and I am currently in the process of formalizing its intellectual property.\r\n\r\nIn addition, I am completing a major research project in the field of psychology, exploring deep-rooted behavioral patterns and psychological schemas that shape individual identity and relationships. This work involves analyzing over 15 psychological constructs and their developmental roots, integrating both theoretical and applied psychological perspectives.\r\n\r\nWhile my formal publishing journey is still developing, I have authored research-based content, presented findings in academic settings, and participated in the early stages of patent documentation. I am committed to producing research that is both rigorous and impactful, especially in fields that intersect human well-being and sustainability.\r\n\r\nI believe that science should not only advance knowledge but also drive practical change. As a Senior Researcher applicant, I look forward to contributing to the Youth Science Journal through careful peer review, constructive feedback, and active engagement with emerging scientific voices.', 6, 'June', 'Facebook ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 06:29:10', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"8\",\"Architecture\":\"4\",\"Arts\":\"10\",\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"10\",\"Chemistry\":\"10\",\"Classics\":\"10\",\"Computer Science\":\"10\",\"Data Science\":\"10\",\"Economics\":\"10\",\"Education\":\"10\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"8\",\"Environmental Science\":\"5\",\"International Relations & Government\":\"5\",\"Linguistics\":\"8\",\"Mathematics\":\"5\",\"Medicine & Public Health\":\"5\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"5\",\"Philosophy\":\"5\",\"Physics & Astrophysics\":\"5\",\"Psychology\":\"5\",\"Public Policy\":\"5\",\"Robotics\":\"5\",\"Sociology & Anthropology\":\"5\"}', 0, NULL),
(64, 'SYSJ0117', 'Ahmed Bahaa El-Din El-Geneidy ', 'Ahmedbahaaeldin2008@gmail.com', '+201550069874', 'Egypt ', 'male', '2008-01-12', 'Amr Ibn Al-Aas Official Language School ', 'G-11', '4', 'Biology', 'A+', 'Mentorship in science is more than just teaching concepts—it’s about guiding students through challenges while keeping their curiosity alive. My journey as a young researcher has shown me that the best mentors combine deep subject knowledge with the ability to inspire resilience. Through my work studying antibiotic resistance in local water sources, I’ve developed both the technical skills and mentoring approach needed to thrive in YSJ’s rigorous academic environment.  \r\n\r\nResearch Foundation & Mentoring Philosophy  \r\nMy hands-on experience with molecular techniques like PCR, gel electrophoresis, and bacterial culturing has given me a strong foundation in biological research. But beyond the lab skills, I’ve learned how to break down complex ideas for peers. When my classmates struggled with statistical analysis, I d simple analogies—comparing p-values to spam filters—that helped them grasp key concepts. This blend of expertise and communication aligns with YSJ’s emphasis on both research excellence and mentorship.  \r\n\r\nAcademic & Mentoring Goals at YSJ  \r\nAt YSJ, I aim to:  \r\n1. Advance my research in sustainable solutions to antibiotic resistance, leveraging your [specific facility/program].  \r\n2. Develop peer mentorship initiatives, such as Failure Forums where students troubleshoot experiments together.  \r\n3. Bridge gaps between high school and undergraduate researchers through collaborative projects.  \r\n\r\nI’m particularly inspired by YSJ’s , which demonstrates how science and mentorship can drive real-world impact.  \r\n\r\nMentoring in Action  \r\nOne of my most rewarding experiences was guiding a teammate through repeated PCR failures. Instead of giving answers, I helped them analyze each step, leading to the discovery of a temperature calibration error. Their eventual success not only strengthened our project but also renewed their excitement for research. Similarly, I co-developed visual lab guides that reduced procedural errors in my school’s science club by 40%, proving that clear, supportive guidance can transform frustration into progress.  \r\n\r\nWhy YSJ?  \r\nYSJ’s culture of collaboration and innovation is the perfect environment to grow as both a researcher and mentor. I’m eager to contribute by fostering a community where young scientists feel empowered to take risks, learn from setbacks, and push the boundaries of what’s possible in STEM.', 'Hi, I noticed we missed the proposal deadline - no worries, these things happen! Lets get you unstuck.\r\n\r\nYouve done great work on [specific aspect of their work], so I know you can nail this proposal. Heres how I can help:', 'As a molecular biology researcher, my work bridges experimental science with science education. I specialize in antimicrobial resistance (AMR) research and developing accessible training tools for early-career scientists.  \r\n\r\nKey Research Areas:  \r\n- Antibiotic resistance profiling in environmental samples  \r\n- Optimization of molecular biology protocols for low-resource settings  \r\n- STEM education research focusing on experimental troubleshooting  \r\n\r\ned Projects:  \r\n\r\n1. Cairo Water AMR Mapping Project (2022-2024)  \r\n- Designed culture-dependent and culture-independent methods to track resistance genes  \r\n- Developed a novel sample concentration technique improving detection limits by 30%  \r\n- *Outputs:*  \r\n  - 1st Author, International Journal of Environmental Microbiology (submitted)  \r\n  - Keynote speaker, Egypt Youth Science Forum 2023  \r\n\r\n2. Microbiology Education Initiative  \r\n- d BioHacks video series (15+ tutorials on common lab challenges)  \r\n- Implemented peer-review system for student research proposals  \r\n- *Impact:*  \r\n  - Adopted by 3 regional STEM programs  \r\n  - Won UNESCO Science Education Prize 2023  \r\n\r\n3. CRISPR-Cas9 for Water Purification (Pilot)  \r\n- Designed gRNAs targeting resistance genes  \r\n- Developed low-cost transformation protocol  \r\n- *Status:* Seeking patent for novel delivery system  \r\n\r\nRecent Presentations:  \r\n- Democratizing Molecular Biology Education - TEDxCairo 2024  \r\n- Citizen Science for AMR Surveillance - International Science Festival  \r\n\r\nResearch Philosophy:  \r\nI believe impactful science requires both technical rigor and knowledge sharing. My work consistently combines bench research with educational innovation, particularly focused on reducing barriers to entry for underrepresented students.  \r\n\r\nFuture Goals:  \r\n- Expand CRISPR applications in environmental biotechnology  \r\n- Develop open-source lab training platforms  \r\n- Establish international youth researcher network', 7, 'Im free from 8 pm to 12 every day ', 'Linkedin ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 12:09:38', '{\"Biology\":\"10\"}', 0, NULL);
INSERT INTO `applications` (`id`, `user_id`, `full_name`, `email`, `contact_number`, `country`, `gender`, `birth_date`, `institution`, `grade_year`, `gpa`, `interest`, `grade_previous`, `first_essay`, `second_essay`, `third_essay`, `hours_commitment`, `time_blocks`, `hear_about`, `commented_file_path`, `cv_path`, `status`, `assigned_to`, `reviewer_suggestion`, `personal_qualifications`, `research_skills`, `analytic_skills`, `mentorship_skills`, `academic_writing`, `academic_performance`, `commitments`, `total_score`, `overall_rating`, `notes`, `submitted_at`, `interest_ratings`, `is_deleted`, `accepted_field`) VALUES
(65, 'SYSJ0138', 'Ganna Mohamed', 'ganna.2223515@stemsharkya.moe.edu.eg', '01098524203', 'Egypt', 'female', '2007-08-25', 'Sharkya STEM School', 'Grade 12', '3.78', '', 'CS: B+', 'I believe that the role of a mentor is not just to explain information or correct mistakes, but it is much deeper than that. The true mentor is the one who knows how to contain the stress and confusion that any student experiences when starting in the field of scientific research, especially in their first experience, and guides them in a supportive manner that fosters passion and curiosity.\r\nI gained a deep understanding of scientific concepts not just from theoretical study, but through real applications I experienced in many research projects. I participated in research that integrates artificial intelligence and environmental sustainability, such as my project on water purification using bio and nano materials, and my other project on AI-based decision support systems, which was published in a scientific journal. These experiences taught me how to deal with challenges and help others when they go through them.\r\nThe most impactful moment for me was when I helped a colleague who was using machine learning algorithms for the first time and felt like she didnt understand anything. So, I started explaining it to her in a simple way, related to things from our reality, like waste classification. When she started to understand and get excited, I felt how the right guidance can completely change a persons experience.\r\nMy goal as a mentor is to  a safe environment for young researchers where they can ask their questions freely, and I encourage them to seek answers on their own. And thats exactly what YSJ provides, an environment that combines guidance, support, and professionalism. Being part of such a community will help me develop myself as a mentor and researcher, and at the same time, be a reason for a young person to love science more and believe in their own abilities.\r\nAcademically, my goal is to integrate artificial intelligence with many other fields, and to  an educational environment for the new generation that fosters critical thinking, not just knowledge. And this aligns perfectly with YSJs goals, which combine real research and early student empowerment.', 'Hello, Team 123!\r\n\r\nMaybe you think youve fallen behind, but the truth is? You still have a chance to do something that will impress us all.\r\nResearch is not a race... its a journey of discovery. But we have to start the journey. And this stage , the idea stage, is the key.\r\nYour idea doesnt have to be perfect from the very first moment. Were here to develop it together.\r\nLet me ask you:\r\nIf there were one problem you dream of solving with science... what would it be?\r\nTake it as a start. Sketch the idea, even if its not complete. And Im here to help you organize the steps, develop them, and turn them into a real project.\r\nWe need a preliminary draft from you within the next 48 hours, not to pressure you, but to start working together.\r\nExcited to see the spark within you turn into real research \r\n\r\nAlways with you,\r\nGanna – Mentor YSJ', 'My passion for data science began when I was learning in the Digital Egypt Pioneers scholarship, through which I was able to apply what I learned in real projects. I worked on models that use artificial intelligence to predict breast cancer and type 1 diabetes. This journey ended with working on a sales forecasting deep learning model with graduate students. These experiences not only enhanced my technical skills but also opened my eyes to the impact of numbers and algorithms in saving lives.\r\nIn the Minerva Research Association program, I worked on a research paper titled Comparative Analysis of AI-Driven Decision Support Systems and Traditional Spreadsheets: Evaluating Accuracy and Consistency in Business Intelligence\" that was among the top 10 research papers in the program, where I used data science to develop a decision support system to help startups avoid failure. This paper is published in the Journal of Science and Technology and on SSRN. It taught me how integrating analysis with realistic goals can lead to significant changes in business outcomes.', 5, 'June 15 – July 15: Participating in the Roots & Roads Data Science Fellowship. (Approx. 10 hours/week)             July – August: Enrolled in Girls Who Code program. (Approx. 3 hours/week)                     July – September: Actively preparing for U.S. university admissions, including college essay writing, scholarship applications, and attending college info sessions and workshops. (Estimated 8–12 hours/week, with flexibility)               Even with these responsibilities, I am confident in my ability to manage my time well and remain committed to fulfilling my mentoring researchers at Youth Science Journal.', 'LinkedIn', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 12:15:57', NULL, 0, 'Computer Science'),
(66, 'SYSJ060', 'Ahmed Mahmoud Gamil', 'amgamil2007@gmail.com', '01063745049', 'Egypt', 'male', '2007-04-11', 'Stem october', 'Junior ', '3.7', 'Biology,Chemistry', 'B+', 'Since enrolling in STEM, I have always been eager to learn everything possible about the research track, whether it was from seniors, clubs, programs, or even Coursera courses. That got me interested in teaching everything I learned to my juniors to help in their nourishment and deepen my understanding of research concepts.\r\nWhen introduced to YSG at the first info session, it has always piqued my interest. Its concept is young researchers, who are underrated by their age, mentoring and fostering younger ones whose ambitions cannot be tamed by simple and less competitive programs. Young researchers, just like myself then, do not need only mentoring and telling them where they are wrong anyone can do this. They are to be shown some care, and that we are their seniors and understand more and have more experience than them by far. Only then will they trust us and show some respect and follow our advice.\r\nNow, the real work will start. Using the previously stated condition of YSG, the young researchers will reach their potential little by little until they submit their final paper, hoping for the highest grades, as the environment pushes them to it.\r\nOne example of this was in my sophomore year, when one of the teams was lagging, searching for the location, while most of the teams started searching for the materials. They faced this problem after being hindered by searching on normal websites, not on professional search engines such as Google Scholar. When their leader asked for help, I simply did not tell him the way directly but made them understand how I reached it and how anyone can reach it by dividing their aim into steps and searching step by step until they reach that one keyword they are going to stick on their search bar, as it indicates perfectly their aim.', 'Dear fellows,\r\nWe saw a great potential in you as a promising researcher, so by wasting it you are failing our expectation. In the same time, there were people who was eager to get accepted and take your place. So, seize the opportunity we gave you while you still have the chance to do so. And remember, deadlines are not here because the time is limited, but to teach you discipline. Hope this will not happen again forcing us to take unnecessary actions. ', 'I completed Writing in sciences course provided by Stanford university.\r\nI completed English for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics course provided by University of Penssylvania.\r\n I completed Chemical Biology: Concepts and Technique course on Coursera, provided by Geneva university.\r\nI received an honorable mention in the International Biology Bowl competition.  \r\nI am currently a mentor at STEM October biology club research track.\r\nI am currently finalizing a systematic review paper about the hyperparathyroidism in men and its broad aspects of symptoms and potential treatment techniques for it probable complications.\r\nI have wrote a paper about the relation between different kinds of diet and its affect on absorption of vitamins and minerals and directly affecting the rate of cellular respiration. \r\nI am currently enrolled in the International Young Researchers Conference medicine and research summer program, Summer 2025 cohort. \r\nI am currently a mentor of organic chemistry at STEM October Chemistry club.\r\nI finished Human anatomy and medical terminology fundamentals course.\r\nI completed Visualizing the Living Body: Diagnostic Imaging provided by Yale university.', 6, '2 weeks in the middle of June and 1 week on the first of August.', 'school', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 18:27:31', '{\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Chemistry\":\"8\"}', 0, 'Biology & Chemistry'),
(67, 'SYSJ0401', 'Eyad Ashraf', 'eyad@gmail.com', '01111605702', 'Egypt', 'male', '2025-07-16', 'STEM', 'Grade Year', 'A', 'Aerospace Engineering,Architecture,Arts', 'Grade of each respective field in previous academic years (if applicable)', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science\r\nMentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science\r\nMentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science', 'Consider youre a YSJ senior researcher. One of your teams, perhaps team 123, has failed to stick to the Research idea proposal deadline. Write a message youd send them via discord to push them to finish their task', 'Please describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\r\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words\r\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words\r\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words\r\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words', 5, 'List down the most significant time blocks you have between the start of June and the end of September.', 'Where did you hear about YSJ?', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0415', 'accept', 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 70, 'Good', 'he is good. He is amzinggg. very very good amazing~~~ best', '2025-07-05 17:04:46', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"1\",\"Architecture\":\"7\",\"Arts\":\"3\"}', 0, 'fied here'),
(68, 'SYSJ0293', 'Ruba Tariq Alahmari ', 'Ruba2008at@gmail.com', '966590331813', 'Saudi Arabia ', 'female', '2008-04-15', 'Ibn Khaldoun Private School – Riyadh', '12', '5.0 / 5.0', '', '5.0 / 5.0', 'Mentorship in scientific research requires not only a deep understanding of scientific concepts but also the ability to motivate and guide students through their challenges. From my experience working on [mention a research project, school project, or scientific topic], I have developed strong problem-solving skills and learned how to support my peers when they face difficulties. This has prepared me to meet YSJ’s high standards for research and mentorship.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to deepen my knowledge in [your field or subject of interest] and enhance my research skills. As for mentorship, I aim to help young researchers overcome obstacles and unlock their full potential. I believe that YSJ’s supportive programs and research environment will provide me with the tools and opportunities to effectively guide and inspire new researchers.\r\n\r\nFor example, I once helped a fellow student who was struggling to understand [specific topic or problem]. By breaking down the problem into simpler parts and encouraging them, I was able to help them grasp the concept and regain their enthusiasm for science. Trrrrtttt ttttt uh mic juju juju hi min bbj bun in j i h g y u hi i i i i hv b in uh u h h ', 'Hey Team 123,\r\n\r\nI noticed that the deadline for the Research Idea Proposal has passed, and we haven’t received your submission yet. It’s really important that we stick to the timelines to keep the project moving forward smoothly.\r\n\r\nPlease prioritize finishing the proposal as soon as possible. If you’re facing any challenges or need support, don’t hesitate to reach out—I’m here to help. Let’s get this done and keep up the great work!\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nRuba Alahmari \r\nSenior Researcher, YSJ\r\n', 'Although I am at the beginning of my research journey, I have a strong passion for learning and exploring scientific topics. I participated in the Riyadh Talents competition, where I was honored to achieve third place. This experience motivated me to develop my skills further and encouraged me to engage more deeply in research activities.\r\n\r\nI am eager to expand my knowledge, learn research methodologies, and contribute to meaningful projects in the future. I believe that being part of YSJ will provide me with the guidance and opportunities I need to grow as a young researcher. Yyy yyy Yyy u I in I u uh u h y b h h b h bh. But  I j I I I h h h h h h h buy in u b b u I u uh huh. I I h u u h u h. \r\nU I I I I \r\n', 9, 'I have a flexible schedule between June and the end of September. I don’t have any major commitments, so I will be available to fully focus on YSJ.', 'What’s up group ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 19:06:18', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"5\",\"Architecture\":\"5\",\"Physics & Astrophysics\":\"5\"}', 0, NULL),
(69, 'SYSJ0350', 'Fareda Ebrahim Arafat', 'faredaarafat1@gmail.com', '+201555561185', 'Egypt ', 'female', '2008-02-17', 'Red Sea STEM ', 'G11', '3.81', 'Biology,Psychology', 'Bio 3.7/4.0', 'Mentorship in scientific research is not just about knowledge—it’s about transforming curiosity into clarity. Through my personal research journey in biotechnology and biomedical engineering, I’ve developed both a technical foundation and a passion for guiding others. I’ve mentored peers during school science fairs, helping them refine hypotheses, understand experimental design, and analyze results. One project involved helping a teammate understand PCR and gel electrophoresis we broke down the process step-by-step until it clicked. The joy they expressed upon presenting confidently made me realize the power of mentorship.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to pursue interdisciplinary research, bridging biology and technology. Mentoring allows me to share this ambition, inspiring others to explore science deeply, not just academically but creatively. At YSJ, the exposure to driven minds and structured mentorship would refine my ability to lead. The platform would allow me to work with curious learners, providing both direction and motivation—key to building confident young researchers.\r\nMentorship in scientific research is not just about knowledge—it’s about transforming curiosity into clarity. Through my personal research journey in biotechnology and biomedical engineering, I’ve developed both a technical foundation and a passion for guiding others. I’ve mentored peers during school science fairs, helping them refine hypotheses, understand experimental design, and analyze results. One project involved helping a teammate understand PCR and gel electrophoresis we broke down the process step-by-step until it clicked. The joy they expressed upon presenting confidently made me realize the power of mentorship.\r\n\r\nMy academic goal is to pursue interdisciplinary research, bridging biology and technology. Mentoring allows me to share this ambition, inspiring others to explore science deeply, not just academically but creatively. At YSJ, the exposure to driven minds and structured mentorship would refine my ability to lead. The platform would allow me to work with curious learners, providing both direction and motivation—key to building confident young researchers.', 'Hey Team 123,\r\n\r\nI hope youre all doing well. I noticed that your research idea proposal hasn’t been submitted yet. Please remember that meeting deadlines is a core part of the YSJ research process—it helps us guide your progress effectively and keeps the entire program running smoothly.\r\n\r\nIf there’s any issue or roadblock you’re facing, don’t hesitate to reach out. I’m here to support you. That said, I’ll need you to finalize and submit your proposal by tomorrow at 8 PM. Let’s get this moving so we can dive into the exciting part—actual research!\r\n\r\nYou’ve got this. Let me know if you need anything!', 'As a high school student deeply passionate about scientific exploration, I’ve been actively involved in research-focused projects that align with real-world challenges, particularly in environmental sustainability and biomedical innovation. My primary areas of interest include water conservation technologies, sensor-based systems, and biomedical engineering.\r\n\r\nOne of my most notable projects involves designing a smart leakage detection system for water pipelines using flow and pressure sensors integrated with microcontrollers like Arduino. This system identifies anomalies in pressure and flow rate, triggers alerts through a mobile app, and deploys a temporary sealing mechanism to reduce water loss—addressing both SDG 6 (Clean Water) and SDG 9 (Industry & Innovation). This project was submitted to a national innovation competition and is currently under technical review.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I’ve worked on STEM-based projects involving basic biomedical sensor integrations (e.g., pulse and temperature monitors), and contributed to local school exhibitions and science fairs with presentations focused on accessible medical technologies.\r\nI’ve participated in STEM clubs and online research bootcamps, learning how to conduct literature reviews, formulate hypotheses, collect data, and analyze results. I’ve also co-led a peer group where we explored emerging science topics and mentored each other in experimental design and scientific writing.\r\n\r\nThese experiences have prepared me for more rigorous research environments and have fueled my aspiration to contribute meaningfully to impactful, interdisciplinary scientific work.', 5, 'nothing', 'My friends', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0415', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 19:26:14', '{\"Biology\":\"7\",\"Psychology\":\"5\"}', 0, NULL),
(70, 'SYSJ0348', 'Jana Mohammad', 'janaghattas38@gmail.com', '01201980828', 'Egypt', 'female', '2009-05-25', 'Gharbiya STEM high school', '10', '4.0', 'Architecture,Biology,Computer Science,Education,Environmental Science', 'Biology A+,  environmental science A, Computer science B+ ', 'For me, mentorship in science has never been just about teaching facts or explaining theories. It’s about walking with others as they face confusion, doubts, or even failure, and helping them see what they’re truly capable of. I’ve seen how one encouraging conversation or a simple explanation can spark confidence in someone who’s struggling. This is why I believe mentorship is just as much emotional as it is intellectual. The quote really resonated with me because it captures what I’ve come to feel through my own research journey: that being a good mentor means knowing your science, yes but more importantly, knowing how to lift others when they’re stuck.\r\nLeading and participating in scientific research work has enabled me to grow both intellectually and as a communicator. One of my most eye-opening experiences so far is my project ThermaVetra Straw, which is working on converting rice straw (one of Egypt’s most prevalent agricultural wastes) into a smart thermal glass that changes transparency with temperature. The idea integrates sustainable innovation with energy efficiency. As we developed the concept, I took the lead in explaining the importance of the project to my team, breaking down the chemistry behind rice straw’s silica content and its transformation into a functional material. By simplifying these ideas, I helped my peers engage with the deeper scientific purpose of our work and gain excitement about research. \r\n\r\nAnother key experience was with OptiAminoVidia, a research initiative exploring the use of discarded amniotic fluid in producing therapeutic eye lenses—providing an native to laser surgery, which often causes long-term damage. I spent months conducting literature reviews and lab discussions, eventually presenting the idea to medical students and faculty at a university. Despite its complexity and novelty, I was able to build their interest and gain valuable feedback. The project has since been accepted for patent application, and I continue to develop it with strong academic support. \r\nThese experiences form my academic and mentoring aspirations: to discover new solutions in sustainable biomedicine and to mentor young researchers into advancing curiosity into accomplishment. The mentorship and training I’ll receive from YSJ will help me grow and serve others. To me, mentorship is about helping actuate the right questions and nudging people to believe in the merit of their ideas.', 'Dear Team 123,\r\nI hope this message finds you well. I’m reaching out to follow up on the Research Idea Proposal, which was due recently. As of now, we have not received your submission.\r\nPlease be reminded that timely submissions are crucial for maintaining the project timeline and ensuring fair progress across all teams. If you are experiencing any difficulties whether technical, organizational, or conceptual do not hesitate to communicate with me. I’m here to support you and help you get back on track.\r\nI kindly encourage you to prioritize finalizing and submitting your proposal as soon as possible. Your contribution is valuable to this process, and I’m confident in your ability to deliver thoughtful and impactful work.\r\nLooking forward to your .\r\nBest regards,  \r\n[Jana Mohammad]  \r\nSenior Researcher, YSJ', 'Over the past few years, I’ve developed a deep passion for scientific research that lies at the intersection of sustainability, biotechnology, and engineering innovation. My research background spans multiple disciplines, including sustainable materials, biomedical innovation, and renewable energy.\r\nOne of my core projects is ThermaVetra Straw, which transforms agricultural waste (rice straw) into smart thermal glass that changes transparency with temperature. This project qualified for the finals of the IEEE IC_SIT international competition and was recognized for its potential in eco-friendly construction.\r\nIn the biomedical field, I am currently pursuing two patents. The first is OptiAminoVidia, a solution that utilizes amniotic fluid to produce therapeutic eye lenses as an native to laser surgery. The second is Dermora, a bioengineered artificial skin d using umbilical cord stem cells, shrimp shells, and aloe vera gel to treat severe burns without the need for grafting from other body parts.\r\nAdditionally, I am participating in Cairo Water Week (CWW) with a project tackling water waste in public areas. The system reuses greywater from ablution and handwashing, filters it through sustainable methods, and redistributes it for irrigation and cleaning using humidity sensors, ESP32 microcontrollers, and recycled materials demonstrating a smart, low-cost solution for urban water conservation.\r\nIn my STEM school, I also led two engineering-based Capstone projects: Sunflower-Like Solar Panels, which track sunlight using recycled materials, and Swung Trunk Bridge, a double-swing bridge optimized for maritime traffic.\r\nThese experiences have not only strengthened my scientific expertise but also taught me how to build impactful solutions that are rooted in both research and real-world needs.', 14, ' I am fully available from the beginning of June until the end of September. I currently have no fixed commitments during this period and can dedicate time consistently to the program whenever needed.', 'linked in. ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0422', 'accept', 5, 14, 7, 10, 15, 8, 10, 69, 'Mid', 'She wrote a sentence that made me unable to understand. Does she understand that she will be the mentor or that she will learn?\r\n The mentorship and training I’ll receive from YSJ will help me grow and serve others. \r\nhere research is good', '2025-07-05 19:36:23', '{\"Architecture\":\"6\",\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Computer Science\":\"7\",\"Education\":\"5\",\"Environmental Science\":\"10\"}', 0, NULL),
(71, 'SYSJ0133', 'Ahmed Khedr', 'ahmedkhedr27777@gmail.com', '01063824960', 'Egypt', 'male', '2009-07-31', 'Alexandria STEM School ', 'G10', '3.6', 'Biology,Neuroscience & Neurobiology,Physics & Astrophysics', 'Biology:: B+, Physics: B+ ', 'Scientific research mentorship requires a strong understanding of the principles as well as the ability to motivate and lead students through their struggles. Read this quote and discuss how your background and experience in scientific research have prepared you adequately to fill yourself into YSJs high standards.\r\n\r\nMy research background is an interlacing of neuroscience, computational science, and outreach — with a common focus on learning through collaboration. I first explored cognitive neuroscience under the Visionary Scholars Program, where I studied the Default Mode Networks role in social cognition. I broke away from computer science with the Entropy Team, developing a Python-based black hole simulation. Today, Im collaborating on the development of a neurotechnological headset that transmits EEG signals wirelessly using Bluetooth to make low-cost brain-computer interface experiments possible — bringing together hardware, signal processing, and neuroscience.\r\n\r\nMentorship is where these technical experiences meet purpose. Ive coached peers through experiment design via Alexandria SEA Team, Resala STEM Helpers, and NeuroInsights Society. Ive also coached peers through EEG preprocessing using MNE-Python and interpreting complex neuroscience data. In one case, I coached a student who was frustrated by noisy brainwaves. I walked them through the concept of bandpass filtering and helped them develop a minimal reproducible code. They ultimately were able to  thoughtful alpha and beta designs — the passion brought to mind the way mentoring can multiply effect.\r\n\r\nAt YSJ, I will contribute to a society that values rigor and empathy equally. I would like to counsel students not merely in practice but in inquiry more deeply: why this hypothesis, this instrument, this model? YSJs culture of collaborative learning, structured mentor pathway, and student-led passion are all ideally matched with helping others to find voice and vision confidence. I, as a Senior Researcher, am eager to support learners who — like me — needed someone to reassure them, Youre on the right track, and heres how we navigate it together.', 'Hey Team 123!\r\n\r\nJust a quick check-in — I noticed the Research Idea Proposal hasn’t been submitted yet. This proposal is the core of your YSJ experience. Without it, we can’t begin mentorship or feedback properly, and that’ll seriously affect the momentum of your whole journey here.\r\n\r\nI really want to see your team move forward, so let’s aim to have it submitted by [ Date Here]. If you’re facing any issues (even small ones), please message me directly — I’m here to help, not judge. Let’s get this step done so we can dive into your actual project — you’ve got potential, and I’d love to help you build on it.\r\n\r\nYouve got this — let’s move! \r\n\r\n— Ahmed Khedr\r\nYSJ Senior Researcher', 'My areas of interest lie at the intersection of neuroscience, neurotechnology, and science communication in youths. I am also pursuing an independent intensive research project on the molecular mechanisms of neuroplasticity, with the aim of determining how processes like long-term potentiation (LTP), synaptic pruning, and brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) expression affect learning, memory, and emotional adaptation in the adolescent. I use systematic review of the literature to formulate experimental models and aim to have a review of this published early next year.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, I am developing an OpenBCI- and Muse-based Bluetooth EEG headset with the aim to decode raw brainwave signals in real time. I employed band-pass filtering, Fourier and wavelet transforms, and feature extraction for decoding patterns in alpha and beta frequency bands. The neurotechnology headset is being developed for portable, low-cost brain-computer interface (BCI) applications in cognitive state monitoring and mental workload research.\r\n\r\nThrough the Entropy Team, I edit and write journal-style scientific content in behavioral science and neuroscience. This exercise enhanced my ability to critically evaluate sources, simplify explanations, and promote scientific literacy within my peer group.\r\n\r\nI also collaborated with the Paradox Team on a simulation project regarding theoretical black holes and relativistic motion. While grounded in physics, this project developed my modeling and coding skills in Python and learned to approach research from a variety of disciplinary frames. \r\n\r\nI also ranked in the top 20% of the Egyptian Computational Sciences Competition, where I gained upper-level experience with data interpretation, algorithmic thinking, and research problem-solving under time constraints.\r\n\r\nThese experiences illustrate my commitment to bridging deep theoretical knowledge and popular scientific practice, aligned with YSJs model of mentorship and innovation.', 14, 'ISEF Research Project (July–September 2025) Title: Creation of a Low-Cost Neurotechnological Headset for Real-Time EEG Monitoring  Within a period of two months, I prototyped and designed a neurotechnology headset that records brainwave activity through dry electrodes and transmits real-time EEG data wirelessly through Bluetooth. The task was to develop an affordable, low-cost solution for cognitive state monitoring with education and attention-based applications in mind. I combined the open-source microcontrollers (i.e., Arduino-compatible boards) with a simple amplification circuit, signal filtering modules, and Bluetooth transmission modules. Initial tests using simulated EEG data yielded stable transmission and successful visualization of signals. The headset is designed to eventually enable classification of cognitive states (e.g., focus, fatigue) using simple machine learning techniques.', 'From a LinkedIn profile ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0418', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 19:52:31', '{\"Biology\":\"9\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"9\",\"Physics & Astrophysics\":\"8\"}', 0, NULL),
(72, 'SYSJ0405', 'Mohammed Mohammed Yousuf Abd Al-Razik', 'mohammed.mo.alqabbani@gmail.com', '+201110008687', 'Egyptian', 'male', '2009-05-14', 'Al-Orman Secondary School for Boys ', '10', '95.5%', 'Aerospace Engineering,Computer Science,Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering),Environmental Science,Mathematics,Physics & Astrophysics,Robotics', 'Math: 96.5% , Science: 100% ,English: 91.5%', 'Mentoring in scientific research not only depends on a deep understanding of concepts, but also requires the ability to communicate effectively, motivate, and guide students throughout their scientific journey, especially when they encounter challenges. Through my research journey and participation in scientific activities, I have gradually developed these skills.\r\n\r\nI participated in the FGS Research Program, where I learned the basics of scientific research methodology in practice, from ing hypotheses and analyzing data, to interpreting and presenting results in an academic style. In addition, I was accepted into the Stanford iGEM Bioengineering Research Program, one of Stanford Universitys prestigious bioengineering programs, where I work as part of a research team on a project that uses synthetic biology to solve real-world problems. These experiences have given me a deeper insight into the nature of scientific research and teamwork.\r\n\r\nI have also participated in several international competitions that have enhanced my scientific and leadership skills, such as the NASA Space Apps Challenge, where I worked on a project on near-Earth objects and the sun the Purple Comet Math Meet (ranked 29th globally) the IYMC, the IAAC, and the International Computer Science Competition.  I also joined The Experiment Digital Leadership in STEM program, which helped me develop my communication and collaboration skills with students from diverse backgrounds and cultures.\r\n\r\nThrough my role at YSJ, I seek to empower younger students to overcome their fear of scientific research and help them develop their research ideas in a structured and clear manner. I aim to simplify scientific concepts, motivate their creativity, and instill confidence in their abilities as young researchers.\r\n\r\nYSJ is the ideal platform to achieve these goals, as it provides an international, youth-led scientific environment that prioritizes quality research and supports school students around the world. Through my role as a Senior Member, I aspire to be part of this ecosystem, providing support to new researchers and guiding them to reach their full potential.\r\n\r\nIn one research program, I helped a colleague who was struggling with data analysis. I explained the basics to him in a simplified manner, and together we reviewed the data and its correlation with the results. Later, he became more confident and began to offer accurate analyses and new ideas.  Situations like these have confirmed to me that mentoring not only makes a better researcher, but also brings out potential that a person may not realize on their own.', 'Hello, Team 123 \r\n\r\nI hope you are all well. I just wanted to remind you that the deadline for submitting your research proposal has passed, and unfortunately, I havent received any submissions yet.\r\n\r\nAs your mentor on this project, Im here to support and assist you, but its crucial that you adhere to the timelines, as this is crucial to properly developing your research project.\r\n\r\nIf you encounter any difficulties—whether in writing your proposal, coordinating between team members, or even choosing a topic—please let me know immediately, and Ill be happy to help you overcome the obstacle.\r\n\r\nWe look forward to hearing from you as soon as possible \r\n\r\nGood luck to you,\r\nMohammed – Senior Researcher – YSJ', 'My research background is still in its early stages, but it is built on a strong passion for science and active participation in international programs and competitions. I am a high school student from Egypt with a deep interest in energy science, space science, artificial intelligence, and bioengineering.\r\n\r\nI participated in the FGS Research Program, where I learned how to structure scientific research, from defining a problem and formulating a hypothesis, through data analysis, to interpreting results and writing a research paper. I also learned about research ethics and scientific analysis methods.\r\n\r\nRecently, I was accepted into the Stanford iGEM Bioengineering Research Program, where I work as part of a team on a synthetic biology project focused on real-world applications of bioengineering. This experience has helped me delve deeper into molecular biology, research design, and collaborative scientific work.\r\n\r\nIn addition, I have participated in several science competitions, including:\r\n\r\nNASA Space Apps Challenge, where I developed a project on near-Earth objects and solar activity using NASA data.\r\n\r\n The Purple Comet Math Meet competition, where my team and I placed 29th globally.\r\n\r\nI have also participated in competitions such as the IYMC, IAAC, and the International Computer Science Competition, which have enhanced my analytical and programming skills.\r\n\r\nAlthough I have not yet published a formal scientific paper, I am currently working on research related to solar-powered mint drying techniques, and I plan to submit it to a young scientists journal soon.\r\n\r\nMy diverse interests and practical experience with research teams make me excited to actively contribute to the Young Scientists Journal, whether as a mentor or a learner.', 10, 'Available all the time', 'Social media ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ0422', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 20:00:00', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"4\",\"Computer Science\":\"10\",\"Engineering (not Aerospace Engineering)\":\"10\",\"Environmental Science\":\"9\",\"Mathematics\":\"10\",\"Physics & Astrophysics\":\"9\",\"Robotics\":\"8\"}', 0, NULL),
(73, 'SYSJ0377', 'Gannah Mohamed', 'mgannah11@gmail.com', '01092633185', 'Egypt ', 'female', '2009-05-18', ' Secondary School for Girls', '11', '3.7', 'Biology,Chemistry', 'I did not study chemistry and biology in Egyptian education until the first year of secondary school, but I participated in scientific competitions related to them, and my grades were B+ or A.', 'As a high school student just beginning my scientific journey, I have not yet deeply studied formal scientific research. However, I’ve already developed strong skills in searching for scientific topics and compiling research papers. One of my early experiences applying this skill was during my participation in the ISEF competition, where I independently researched and structured a paper on a topic of interest. This experience helped me understand the value of accurate information, organization, and persistence foundational qualities in research mentorship.\r\nI’ve also found fulfillment in supporting others academically. I’ve helped peers solve problems related to their studies or projects, and whenever I possess the knowledge or experience, I never hesitate to assist those around me. I believe mentorship begins with empathy, and I try to provide that whenever I can.\r\nMy academic goal is to pursue a degree in medicine, as I dream of conducting research that could help treat hearing loss not with external devices, but through innovative physiological methods. This dream, which l have held since childhood, is what drives my passion for science and learning.\r\nOne of my goals in life too is to leave a lasting impact on the hearts and minds of everyone I interact with, so that my presence becomes a meaningful and valuable memory.\r\nI always feel genuinely happy when I share useful knowledge with someone who truly needs it rather than just offering opinions with no real benefit.\r\nI sincerely hope I can continue doing that throughout my life.\r\n', 'Hey team! 🌟\r\nSince were all partners in this journey, I’ve noticed that our drive and creativity might not be as strong as they used to be. And that’s okay  pressure can sometimes wear us down. But let’s not forget why we started. Our goal isn’t just success, it’s excellence. We’re aiming for the top  and even if we don’t reach it right away, what matters is that we give it everything we’ve got so we never regret missing an opportunity.\r\nI’m sure you’ll complete the task in the best way possible because that’s who you are. I believe in you, I’m proud of you, and I’ll always be waiting for your best work. Let’s do this! 💪\r\n\r\n', 'Since I’m still at the beginning of my research journey, I don’t have a lot of experience to share yet. But I always believe in being honest, clear, and respectful and I trust that the person reading this application will understand that.\r\nI worked on a project for ISEF about the dangers of phosphine gas and how to treat people who try to harm themselves using aluminum phosphide tablets. But we couldn’t continue the project because doing the lab experiments was too difficult. I also worked with a friend on a research paper about environmental sustainability. Our idea was to protect sea creatures from suffocating because of harmful gases and plastic waste.I’m really excited to learn more and gain real research experience with YSJ. I hope I can be part of new projects and grow through them \r\nI also had the opportunity to speak with a professor at the Faculty of Science about the scientific research I hope to carry out in the future.\r\nShe thought it was a brilliant idea and expressed her hope that it would one day be implemented in real life.\r\n\r\n', 5, 'From 15July to10 August', 'By student group on telegram ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ052', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 20:09:04', '{\"Biology\":\"8\",\"Chemistry\":\"7\"}', 0, NULL),
(74, 'SYSJ0366', 'Sama Elbanna', 'samasls2008@gmail.com', '01150911197', 'Egypt', 'female', '2008-03-19', 'Alexandria STEM school', 'Grade 11 (Turning grade 12)', '3.98', '', 'Biology: A (G10 and G11). I am a current scholar at Pioneer as well and for my respective assignments I have got a 100% so far.', 'The most challenging aspect of the first research experience, in my opinion, is the challenge to question and critique existing studies and trace how my thinking evolves. For instance, a common challenge many junior researchers face is finding their voice and confidently articulating their hypothesis in their research .\r\nI have previously assisted younger peers during their research programs as Pioneer, and many of them struggled to express confidence in their bold claims in these situations and focus on their objectives through mind-body linking. This is more efficient as the process develops linking their observed details during background research and analysis with their thoughts and interests in the research topic. When they begin to organize their ideas in this way,  it not only makes the research more engaging but also ensures it remains relevant to the researcher themselves, which keeps them motivated through the process. \r\nI learned this technique from my Pioneer during my research. He taught me to connect my thoughts with my observations, which has helped me develop my method. Additionally, he always made the research feel less intimidating and more like a process through which I could grow.\r\nThat is how I aspire to be as a mentor at YSJ. My goal is to inspire young researchers by thinking critically about their work design and the expression of their ideas. I believe that combining understanding with this mindset can make the research process more meaningful and less overwhelming.\r\n', 'Greetings team 123, \r\nI have seen that you have unfortunately failed to submit your Research proposal before the deadline. While I do understand that some potential emergencies might come up, please make sure you finish your paperwork early and adjust your time accordingly. If anything comes up, notfiy me beforehand so we can extend your deadline accordingly. Late submissions without prior notice are not acceptable by all means. \r\nThank you for your consideration!\r\nRegards,\r\nSama Elbanna', 'My research focus during my cohort was to investigate the effects of physical activity and exercise on clinical populations. This included designing a comparative analysis of exercise training for a specific clinical group.\r\nOne of my top priorities was to present a relevant and practical approach that could help researchers gain a better understanding of a cardiopulmonary condition known as cardiogenic pulmonary edema. Throughout my research, I wanted to evaluate whether exercise training could be beneficial for patients with this disease. This condition often results in significant hospitalization and may be exacerbated by exercise due to heavy cardiogenic burden and hydrostatic stress, which caused a challenge for implementing an exercise-based solution.\r\nTo design a credible approach, I returned to the fundamentals and established my ground purpose, which was to develop a method that could ultimately enhance pulmonary rehabilitation and improve the efficiency of heart muscle pumping. To achieve this, I researched heart failure and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), both of which produce symptoms similar to pulmonary edema, such as dyspnea and a decline in lower body mobility. I constructed my protocol based on existing exercise assessments related to these conditions. While they provided an excellent starting point, I needed to implement several modifications in those protocols, as pulmonary edema presents its own risks in some cases, exercise could exacerbate the condition. Therefore, one of the key modifications in my protocol was to comparatively lower the exercise intensity to prevent lung damage. My finalized randomized controlled trial (RCT) involved an analytical comparison of treadmill aerobic walking and recumbent cycling, enabling researchers to understand the activated muscle groups and pulmonary function under fluid stress conditions.\r\n', 5, 'August 23rd: DSAT exam, September 6th: IELTS exam', 'Whatsapp and LinkedIn', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0418', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 20:21:08', NULL, 0, 'Public Health');
INSERT INTO `applications` (`id`, `user_id`, `full_name`, `email`, `contact_number`, `country`, `gender`, `birth_date`, `institution`, `grade_year`, `gpa`, `interest`, `grade_previous`, `first_essay`, `second_essay`, `third_essay`, `hours_commitment`, `time_blocks`, `hear_about`, `commented_file_path`, `cv_path`, `status`, `assigned_to`, `reviewer_suggestion`, `personal_qualifications`, `research_skills`, `analytic_skills`, `mentorship_skills`, `academic_writing`, `academic_performance`, `commitments`, `total_score`, `overall_rating`, `notes`, `submitted_at`, `interest_ratings`, `is_deleted`, `accepted_field`) VALUES
(75, 'SYSJ0194', 'John Yousef', 'yousefnaeemgandey@gmail.com', '01141434555', 'Egypt', 'male', '2009-03-13', 'STEM High School for Boys - 6th of October', '12th grade', '4.0', 'Aerospace Engineering,Mathematics', 'Math: A', 'As a researcher, I started my career in research, struggling in the processes of research because I didn’t find a dedicated, suitable advisor to guide me in the research process. So I struggled with working on research in my first experiences—the capstone of the first semester. Since then, I decided never to repeat this experience with any junior researchers I will supervise in the future. Every time, I was obligated to work on the capstone of the first semester by testing every method of research by myself to discover the best research methodologies for each type of research.\r\nMy experience in math, I have studied more than five math references, especially in number theory, the most common place for conducting math research, and read 10 math articles about controversial topics like paradoxes and millennium problems. For my expertise in aerospace engineering, I am currently studying aerospace engineering references, such as Fundamentals of Aerodynamics and other books, and reading articles about it to be up to date with recently published discoveries, due to the nature of my role in the engineering club.\r\nAs the aerospace track head right now, I mentored juniors in aerodynamics and fluid mechanics principles. Those who were struggling with physics, although they demonstrated their passion in it, didn’t find the guidance they needed. But now, they are about to author their first article in aerospace engineering.\r\nAlso, as a researcher right now, I have both authored and co-authored more than five research papers. I co-authored 4 papers in capstone, 3 of them graded A+, and authored two papers as independent work. One of which was the final project of the engineering club, and it was graded as one of the best three papers after the evaluation.\r\nMy goals as a senior at YSJ, I plan to use weekly progress reviews (like milestones) to help juniors iterate efficiently, to always give them tasks that will be required at some time to make them involved in the research and excited to pass each task to take the upcoming one. I also aim to provide them with resources that may help them with research because of my experience in both fields.\r\nFinally, I want to conclude by saying that I would love to merge the experience I have gained in research with my knowledge and passion in math and aerospace engineering with junior researchers.', 'Hey team, just a quick reminder that the deadline for submitting your research idea proposal has already passed. This is a critical part of the process, and missing deadlines like this puts the whole project timeline at risk. Please prioritize getting it done and sent to me by XXX. If there’s something blocking your progress, or you are struggling with any obstacles, let me know now so we can sort it out. Let’s get this back on track asap.', 'My research expertise lies predominantly in the field of engineering, with a focus on environmental and aerospace engineering in which I have co-authored up to four research papers in environmental engineering as a collaborative work for scholar projects—Capstone. Also, I have authored research paper in aerospace engineering as an independent work. \r\nThrough the Capstone projects, we addressed environmental engineering challenges through applied mathematics. For CuraAqua’s wastewater treatment system project, I derived mathematical models from experimental data to optimize treatment stages, then I documented the results in a handout. In the renewable energy project, I made an efficiency mathematical evaluation for the system, where I have mathematically analyzed system dimensions to maximize efficiency that achieved efficiency above 90%, authoring the optimization report in the handout. Both projects earned A+ ratings for their rigorous technical foundations. These hands-on experiences honed my mathematical modeling, systems integration, and teamwork abilities. \r\nI have authored an aerospace engineering paper, a review paper, about wake management, the concept of vorticity and circulation of air making a turbulent flow beyond the vehicle due to its design or its structure, where I have discussed in this paper the history of vehicles and the development of the design. This paper took the third place in the engineering papers evaluation at perceived season of the engineering club after making a presentation to explain the findings.   \r\nCurrently, I am leading the aerospace engineering track member through the season by conducting sessions to explain the fluid mechanics and aerodynamics fundamentals and CFD simulation tools (Ansys) to help them to make research in vehicle structural optimization using computational tools.\r\nBesides, I have authored a computational physics research paper about the stability analysis in zero angular momentum configurations of the four-body problem, where I have used computational tools like python visuals and data analysis libraries.', 9, 'SAT preparation, commitment with other scholar activities (physics, engineering, and math clubs), admission necessities (writing college essays)', 'From WhatsApp', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0422', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 21:00:02', '{\"Aerospace Engineering\":\"3\",\"Mathematics\":\"7\"}', 0, 'Mathematics'),
(76, 'SYSJ054', 'Yusuf Abdullah ', 'youssef.1223065@stemalex.moe.edu.eg', '+201557375977', 'Egypt', 'male', '2007-09-15', 'Alexandria STEM school ', 'G11', '3.8/4.0', 'Neuroscience & Neurobiology', 'Biology, including neuroscience, A and B+ for the first and second years in the high school, respectively. ', 'Every person develops unique interests shaped by different life experiences that impact the decisions taken. \r\nRegarding myself, I am a person who is looking for self-development driven by passion for neuroscience to make great achievements, including competing in the IYNA neuroscience competition and ITC with a project related to botany. Additionally, I engaged in biological programs, including the EduQuirk research program, which was the first step towards scientific research, and then the Tech Genius Institute research program, which introduced me to the fundamentals of biotechnology. Also, it was my first academic writing experience, as I authored my first research paper. Furthermore, being a student in the STEM community, where completing four semester-long projects helped me acquire enormous skills, including leadership and research. Additionally, co-writing four literature reviews for these projects improves academic writing skills. These experiences laid the foundation for starting my research into a neuroscience disease, as I have worked on a solution for myasthenia gravis to find a treatment providing better quality of life for patients living with the disease. Meanwhile, I am currently publishing a research paper on the findings. \r\nUltimately, as a person who aspires to make an impact wherever he exists, being a part of the school biology club provides the opportunity for me to educate my surrounding colleagues about biology and link the curriculum to the semester-long project. My promotion to be the vice leader gives me the opportunity to improve my leadership skills, leading to founding a neuroscience community to educate those who have a passion for neuroscience, introducing the field, simplifying its concepts, and exploring the basics of scientific research. \r\nMentors, in my opinion, are the bridges that help those who lack some knowledge to overcome challenges. Guiding them through research, finding the right sources, and improving their writing, making it more scientific. Moreover, my passion for biology motivates me to continuously expand my understanding beyond the curriculum, which makes me able to guide the freshmen, even when they are preparing for the acceptance test, to study and understand complex biological concepts. Around 40 students were accepted, including 10 who got a high academic grade during their first year.\r\nThe gained experience was essential in founding the neuroscience community to supervise the younger members while preparing the content and enriching them with experience in academic writing and scientific research.\r\n', 'I hope this message finds you well. \r\nIt is a surprise to see that you missed the deadline, as all of you applied with passion for a specific field. Also, you have been shortlisted out of numerous applicants for your interests and skills. For every accepted researcher, many who also have interests and skills, on the other hand, have been rejected due to small gaps found in their profile. So be responsible for the position you occupied. \r\nYou have one final 24 hours given to submit the delayed proposal. In this time, feel free to ask about anything that you have a misconception about that may have caused the delay. \r\nTake into consideration that delays at any stage, even the early ones, can affect your entire timeline. Also, any other delay will affect your grade, something that none of you hope will happen. I wish to see strong results to make up for that delay.\r\n', 'Humanity is likened to a race, where we all compete to excel in our position, which requires ongoing self-improvement because of the continuous enhancement of the world around us. \r\nRegarding myself, as a person who is motivated by his passion for neuroscience to make great attainments, including competing in the IYNA neuroscience competition, the first experience in neuroscience inspired me to deepen my knowledge of the field. I started by self-studying neuroscience through academic references, educational websites, and explanatory videos. Additionally, engaging in biological programs, including the EduQuirk research program, is the first step towards scientific research. Then I deepened my knowledge of neuroscience through the Neuro Insights Society program, where I studied different aspects of the nervous system structure, and the Tech Genius Institute research program, which introduced me to the fundamentals of biotechnology. This is besides being exposed to the first real academic writing and research project experience, as I authored my first research paper, which is under development to be published. Furthermore, being a student in the STEM community, completing four semester-long projects helped me acquire enormous skills, including leadership and research. Also, co-writing four literature reviews for these projects improves academic writing skills. These experiences laid the foundation to start my own research, beyond the school capstone for a neuroscience disease, as I have worked on a solution for myasthenia gravis, aiming to find a treatment to provide better life quality for patients living with the disease. Meanwhile, I am currently publishing two research papers about the findings and the disease overview and also applying for a patent. \r\nUltimately, as a person who aspires to have an impact wherever he exists, this led me to found a neuroscience community to educate those who have a passion for neuroscience, introducing the field and simplifying its concepts.', 12, 'Despite studying the school curriculum, I have no commitments.', 'The whatsapp channel', NULL, NULL, 'approved', 'SYSJ0418', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 21:00:39', '{\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"9\"}', 0, 'Neuroscience & Neurobiology'),
(77, 'SYSJ0376', 'Mariam Amir ', 'mariamamirhanna4@gmail.com', '01204719255', 'Egypt', 'female', '2007-04-26', 'The Model School ', '12', '93% ≈ 4', '', '4', 'Some students fear data. Others fear the unknown. As a young researcher and mentor, I’ve learned to meet both with curiosity—and help others do the same.\r\nMy journey in scientific research began with questions: How can waste become a solution? Can technology decode environmental damage? These questions led me to research carbon-silica nanocomposites for bone scaffolds, develop AI models to predict microplastic pollution, and  platforms to promote recycling and rainwater harvesting. But the turning point wasnt publishing or awards—it was when I saw my first student’s eyes light up after finally grasping how brain synapses transmit signals. That moment redefined research for me: from isolated discovery to shared transformation.\r\nI believe mentorship is an act of translation—turning complexity into clarity and fear into fascination. As a science tutor, I guided students through confusing concepts in neuroscience, biology, and environmental systems. Using visual storytelling, analogies from daily life, and gamified feedback, I helped students who once dreaded science become eager explorers. One of them later messaged me: I want to be a climate scientist like you. That, to me, is success.\r\nYSJ’s mission to uphold rigorous standards while empowering young minds speaks directly to my dual passion: research and mentorship. I’m excited to contribute to a community where I can help others ask bold questions, embrace messy data, and celebrate small insights. I see myself not just leading in research, but building bridges—between confusion and understanding, between fear and excitement.\r\nIn every mentee, there is a future scientist. I hope to be the voice that tells them, “Yes, you belong here.”', 'If I were a YSJ Senior Researcher and Team 123 missed the proposal deadline, I wouldn’t just remind them—I’d re-ignite their purpose. Here’s how I’d approach it:\r\n\r\n🧠💬 Message to Team 123 via Discord:\r\nHey Team 123 🌱,\r\nYour silence is louder than you think—and it’s not like you.\r\nDeadlines at YSJ aren’t just dates they’re launchpads. You’re standing at the edge of an idea that could change how we see the world—and I won’t let it go to waste.\r\nMissing this proposal means missing the opportunity to take your first real step as researchers. So, here’s what we’ll do:\r\n1. You have 24 hours to regroup and submit your research idea.\r\n2. If youre stuck,  me a DM—I’ll walk you through. No judgment. Just progress.\r\n3. Remember: research doesn’t have to be perfect. But it has to begin.\r\nI believe in your minds. Now show me your momentum.\r\n— Mariam,\r\nSenior Researcher  Biology & Environmental Science 💡🌍', 'From the bustling labs of Egypt’s National Research Centre to late-night Zoom calls with researchers across time zones, my research journey has been anything but ordinary. I’ve always been drawn to the intersection where science meets purpose—where ideas are not just explored but applied to improve lives.\r\n\r\nCurrently, I’m honored to be working with Dr. Sakthi at Brown University through the Talaria Summer Institute, diving into climate-focused research that explores technologys role in building a more sustainable future. This builds on my earlier work, from crafting an AI-powered honeypot to combat cyber threats under the guidance of a Stanford-affiliated mentor, to developing carbon-silica nanocomposites for bone scaffolds at a biotechnology lab.\r\n\r\nBut for me, research goes beyond the lab. It’s a way to answer urgent questions—How can AI help us protect marine ecosystems? What if a website could inspire communities to turn kitchen waste into energy? These questions shaped my projects: from an AI bot predicting microplastic hotspots, to a smart recycling platform with gamified tools for public engagement.\r\n\r\nI’ve also written extensively—publishing environmental articles, five educational books, and a climate adaptation study that earned me a top spot out of 37,500 global participants in the Climate Science Olympiad.\r\n\r\nBeyond titles and metrics, what drives me is impact. Whether tutoring younger students, co-founding an opportunity-sharing platform for youth, or volunteering at hospitals and environmental campaigns, I see science as a tool for empowerment. My work is grounded in a simple belief: research should reach beyond papers—it should plant trees, solve real problems, and inspire others to act.', 12, 'N/A', 'My friend ', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ052', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 21:01:50', NULL, 0, NULL),
(78, 'SYSJ0108', 'Nazdar İşçi', 'nisci26@my.aci.k12.tr', '05523234744', 'Türkiye', 'female', '2007-11-11', 'American Collegiate Institute', '12', '94.3/100', 'Computer Science,Data Science,Neuroscience & Neurobiology', 'It would be the same', 'Mentorship in science isn’t just about knowing the material. It’s about standing beside someone when they feel stuck or unsure and helping them see what they’re capable of, even when they can’t see it themselves.\r\nThroughout my research journey, there were moments I felt lost  coding EEG data, trying to make sense of signal noise, struggling to understand the patterns in Alzheimer’s progression in one of my research projects. But through those moments, I learned how powerful it is to keep going and how much of research is about patience and problem solving. These experiences didn’t just make me stronger in science, they made me want to help others feel less alone in their learning.\r\nI want to be a mentor who makes the process feel less intimidating and more human.  In the English for Everyone club I co founded, I work with children affected by the earthquake in Turkey. Many felt like they weren’t smart enough to learn English, or that school had left them behind. I led a team of volunteers to  lessons that were creative and joyful  and slowly, they started believing in themselves again. That experience showed me how mentorship is about more than teaching , it’s about making someone feel seen.\r\nAt YSJ, I hope to  that same feeling for student researchers. I’ve learned a lot from my own experience writing scientific articles. I’ve worked on Alzheimer’s research using machine learning and EEG signals, and I’ve done lab based chemistry projects on topics like buffering capacity and pH dependent absorbance. But more importantly, I know what it’s like to be new to research, to doubt yourself, to rewrite a paragraph ten times, to wonder if your ideas are “enough.” That’s where mentors can make all the difference.\r\nWhat excites me most about YSJ is its focus on student led research and the full process, not just the final product, but the editing, revising, and growing along the way. I want to support young researchers not just with their science, but in helping them feel confident enough to share it.\r\nIn the end, I believe mentorship is about walking next to someone, not ahead of them, and reminding them that their questions matter. That’s the kind of mentor I hope to be at YSJ.', 'Hi! I noticed that your research idea proposal hasn’t been submitted yet. I totally understand that sometimes things get overwhelming or ideas take longer to form than expected. But we do need to move forward to stay on track with the next phase of the project.\r\nCan you please try to finalize and send it in by tomorrow evening at the latest? If there’s anything blocking you, whether its uncertainty about the topic, team dynamics, or even just needing someone to look things over feel free to reach out me. I’m happy to help however I can.', 'Over the past two years, I’ve led and participated in multiple research projects across neuroscience, machine learning, and chemistry. My main research focus lies at the intersection of computational methods and real world health challenges.\r\nOne of my most in depth projects explored early-stage Alzheimer’s prediction using EEG data and machine learning. After volunteering at Alzheimer for Youth, I began independently studying EEG signals and neurological biomarkers. I implemented a full pipeline from data preprocessing to classification using algorithms like Random Forest and LightGBM. This project was submitted to the SARC competition and is currently under revision by me for potential publication.\r\nAdditionally, I’ve written scientific papers about energy transfer by sound and exoplanet detection from Tess and Kepler data. My writing experience also extends to blog-style scientific outreach articles that break down complex topics like brain-computer interfaces and neuroplasticity.\r\nIn chemistry, I conducted an IB Internal Assessment investigating how pH affects the absorbance of anthocyanins in red cabbage. I also carried out a separate project measuring the buffering capacity of vinegar, which deepened my understanding of titration, equilibria, and real world applications of acid-base chemistry.\r\nThrough these experiences, I’ve developed both technical skills (Python, EEG signal analysis, ML pipelines, spectrophotometry) and soft skills (science communication, leadership, and mentorship). I’m passionate about using scientific inquiry not only to solve complex problems but also to inspire curiosity and independent research in others.\r\n', 15, 'Through summer I have two internships, one till the end of summer and other till the end of september', 'google', NULL, NULL, 'rejected', 'SYSJ052', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-07-05 21:02:38', '{\"Computer Science\":\"9\",\"Data Science\":\"6\",\"Neuroscience & Neurobiology\":\"8\"}', 0, NULL),
(79, 'SYSJ0412', 'Ahmed Saif Eldeen', 'ahmedsaifeldeen1314@gmail.com', '+201091310012', 'Egypt', 'male', '2008-08-13', 'STEM', 'adsaf', '8', 'Arts', '5', 'Please describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit', 'Please describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit', 'Please describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and/or patents) you have been involved in, and/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word LimitPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.