('SYSJ0332', '{\"full-name\":\"Zhassulan Imash\",\"email-address\":\"zhasco10@gmail.com\",\"contact-number\":\"+77089150504\",\"country\":\"Kazakhstan\",\"birth-date\":\"2008-05-29\",\"institution\":\"BIL\",\"grade-year\":\"2025\",\"gpa\":\"5.0\",\"interest\":[\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy,Computer Science,Data Science,Robotics\"],\"interest_ratings\":{\"Business, Entrepreneurship, & Strategy\":\"10\",\"Computer Science\":\"10\",\"Data Science\":\"8\",\"Robotics\":\"7\"},\"grade-previous\":\"5.0\",\"first-essay\":\"\",\"second-essay\":\"\",\"third-essay\":\"\",\"hours_commitment\":\"\",\"time_blocks\":\"\",\"hear_about\":\"\"}', '[]', '2025-07-02 11:37:01'),
('SYSJ0333', '{\"full-name\":\"EYad\",\"email-address\":\"email@email.com\",\"contact-number\":\"\",\"country\":\"Egypt\",\"gender\":\"male\",\"birth-date\":\"2025-07-16\",\"institution\":\"STEM\",\"grade-year\":\"2020\",\"gpa\":\"A+\",\"interest\":[\"\"],\"grade-previous\":\"\",\"first-essay\":\"Mentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\\r\\n\\r\\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science\\r\\nMentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\\r\\n\\r\\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science\\r\\nMentorship in scientific research requires a comprehensive understanding of the concepts and the ability to motivate and direct students as they go through their difficulties. Analyze this quote and discuss how your experiences and knowledge in scientific research have prepared you enough to fit yourself into YSJs high standards.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn your response, state your academic and mentoring goals, explaining how some aspects of YSJ would help you direct young researchers toward their potential.\\r\\n\\r\\nFurthermore, give examples of situations where you have helped learners wade through complex problems to aid their growth and excitement for science\",\"second-essay\":\"Consider youre a YSJ senior researcher. One of your teams, perhaps team 123, has failed to stick to the Research idea proposal deadline. Write a message youd send them via discord to push them to finish their task\",\"third-essay\":\"Please describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and\\/or patents) you have been involved in, and\\/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\\r\\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and\\/or patents) you have been involved in, and\\/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\\r\\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and\\/or patents) you have been involved in, and\\/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\\r\\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and\\/or patents) you have been involved in, and\\/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\\r\\nPlease describe your research background, including your areas of expertise, the research projects (e.g., papers, projects, and\\/or patents) you have been involved in, and\\/or any publications or presentations resulting from your research. (Word Limit: 150-300 words)\",\"hours_commitment\":\"3\",\"time_blocks\":\"time blo\",\"hear_about\":\"\"}', '{\"research_files\":[{\"name\":\"2.png\",\"path\":\"uploads\\/SYSJ0333\\/drafts\\/2.png\",\"size\":29993,\"type\":\"image\\/png\"}],\"commented_files\":[{\"name\":\"prices.pdf\",\"path\":\"uploads\\/SYSJ0333\\/drafts\\/prices.pdf\",\"size\":395064,\"type\":\"application\\/pdf\"}]}', '2025-07-02 11:06:43'),
('SYSJ0334', '{\"full-name\":\"Mariam Khaled \",\"email-address\":\"khaledmariam022@gmail.com\",\"contact-number\":\"01020331322\",\"country\":\"Egypt\",\"gender\":\"female\",\"birth-date\":\"1999-01-01\",\"institution\":\"Ain shams university \",\"grade-year\":\"2023\",\"gpa\":\"3.20\",\"interest\":[\"Biology,Chemistry,Medicine & Public Health\"],\"interest_ratings\":{\"Biology\":\"10\",\"Chemistry\":\"8\",\"Medicine & Public Health\":\"10\"},\"grade-previous\":\"biology 60\\\\60, chemistry 57.5\\\\60, Dentistry 80%\",\"first-essay\":\"This statement deeply resonates with my approach to scientific research and leadership. I believe mentorship is not only about imparting technical knowledge but also about nurturing curiosity, resilience, and confidence in young researchers as they face uncertainty and challenges.\\r\\n\\r\\nThroughout my academic journey in dentistry and my active involvement in training roles, I have acquired a solid foundation in both research methodology and student-centered mentorship. My goal is to become a mentor who not only transfers knowledge but also **inspires students to think critically, ask bold questions, and persist through obstacles.**\\r\\n\\r\\nDuring my time at Ain Shams University, I led several initiatives through the **Faculty of Dentistry\\u2019s Student ** and as part of the **Egyptian Association of Dental Students**, where I designed and facilitated educational workshops, including those related to **biomedical science and evidence-based dentistry**. These sessions often required breaking down complex topics\\u2014such as clinical trial design, data interpretation, and ethical considerations\\u2014into accessible language and interactive discussions. I observed that when learners felt safe to question and make mistakes, their engagement and creativity flourished.\\r\\n\\r\\nOne example that stands out involved mentoring a group of students preparing a presentation on the microbiological impact of dental implants. They initially struggled with structuring their research and interpreting scientific papers. I helped them develop a mind map to organize their thoughts and taught them how to critically analyze sources. Over time, their confidence grew, and they presented their findings at a university seminar. Seeing them transition from confusion to clarity affirmed my belief in patient, personalized mentorship.\\r\\n\\r\\nMy academic goal is to continue contributing to interdisciplinary research that bridges clinical application and academic knowledge, while my mentoring goal is to support students in identifying their strengths and turning confusion into curiosity. At YSJ, I\\u2019m particularly drawn to your **emphasis on inclusive, reflective teaching** and your **commitment to student-led learning**, which aligns perfectly with my mentoring philosophy.\\r\\n\\r\\nYSJ\\u2019s environment\\u2014where mentorship is considered a reciprocal and evolving relationship\\u2014would empower me to both give and grow. The university\\u2019s active research culture, combined with its focus on **empowering students from diverse backgrounds**, makes it an ideal place for me to contribute meaningfully while developing further as a research mentor.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn conclusion, I view mentorship not as a position of authority, but as a shared journey of learning, critical thinking, and discovery. With my background in scientific research and my genuine passion for guiding others, I am confident in my ability to meet YSJ\\u2019s high standards and to contribute to shaping the next generation of thoughtful, ethical, and inquisitive researchers.\",\"second-essay\":\"Hey Team 123 \\ud83d\\udc4b\\r\\n\\r\\nI noticed that your **Research Idea Proposal** hasn\\u2019t been submitted yet, and we\\u2019ve already passed the deadline. I understand things can get overwhelming, but meeting timelines is a critical part of your research journey\\u2014and the longer we delay, the more pressure you\\u2019ll face later in the process.\\r\\n\\r\\nLet\\u2019s get this back on track. Please prioritize finalizing your proposal **within the next 48 hours**. If you\\u2019re facing specific challenges or stuck on anything, don\\u2019t hesitate to reach out\\u2014we\\u2019re here to support you, not just supervise you.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis stage sets the tone for everything that follows, so let\\u2019s aim for progress, not perfection. Im counting on your commitment.\\r\\n\\r\\nLooking forward to your submission soon!\\r\\n\\u2014 \\\\[Mariam Khaled], YSJ Research Lead\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\",\"third-essay\":\"\",\"hours_commitment\":\"\",\"time_blocks\":\"\",\"hear_about\":\"\"}', '[]', '2025-07-02 12:01:00'),
('SYSJ0335', '{\"full-name\":\"Irmak Melek \\u0130\\u00e7\\u00f6z\",\"email-address\":\"iirmakmelek@gmail.com\",\"contact-number\":\"+90 553 936 20 37\",\"country\":\"Turkey\",\"gender\":\"female\",\"birth-date\":\"2007-10-22\",\"institution\":\"Youth-Z\",\"grade-year\":\"12\",\"gpa\":\"85\\/100\",\"interest\":[\"\"],\"grade-previous\":\"\",\"first-essay\":\"The quote emphasizes a reality I have personally lived through: that mentorship in scientific research is not just about knowing the material, it\\u2019s about knowing the person. It\\u2019s about recognizing when a student is stuck not just due to a lack of understanding, but due to a lack of confidence. Its about giving direction without taking away their agency. My journey in science, especially through leadership roles and collaborative projects, has been shaped by this philosophy and its what I hope to bring to YSJ.\\r\\nThroughout my academic career, I\\u2019ve balanced my passion for research with a deep commitment to mentoring. As the founder of my school\\u2019s robotics club and the leader of our science magazine, I\\u2019ve d inclusive environments where younger students feel safe to ask questions, explore ideas, and even make mistakes. From teaching the basics of programming to helping students debug a code they couldn\\u2019t quite crack, I\\u2019ve found joy in breaking down complex concepts into approachable challenges. These experiences taught me that motivation grows not just from achievement, but from being understood and encouraged when the path gets difficult.\\r\\nOne moment that stands out was during a schoolwide sustainability project I co-led. A younger teammate was overwhelmed by the data collection process and nearly ped out of the initiative. Instead of pushing them to just figure it out, I sat down with them, helped them break the task into smaller steps, and guided them through creating visual patterns from their raw numbers. Their transformation from anxious to enthusiastic reminded me that mentorship isn\\u2019t about having all the answers. It\\u2019s about asking the right questions at the right time.\\r\\nYSJ\\u2019s emphasis on high standards in both academic excellence and mentorship aligns with what I value most. The institution\\u2019s interdisciplinary environment and its encouragement of student-led initiatives would allow me to both sharpen my scientific rigor and nurture future changemakers. My academic goal is to further develop my skills in artificial intelligence and smart technologies, while my mentoring goal is to build bridges between early learners and complex research by simplifying, guiding, and inspiring.\\r\\nAt YSJ, I would be excited not only to contribute to scientific inquiry but to build mentorship networks that encourage persistence, creativity, and curiosity. Because sometimes, what students need most is not the right answer, but someone who believes they\\u2019re capable of finding it.\",\"second-essay\":\"Hey Team 123 \\ud83d\\udc4b\\r\\nJust checking in, Ive noticed your Research Idea Proposal hasn\\u2019t been submitted yet. The deadline has already passed, and this puts your timeline (and potentially your eligibility for next phase work) at risk.\\r\\nI understand things can get hectic, but at this point its crucial that you finalize and submit your proposal today. If youre stuck on something or need quick feedback, ping me here Im happy to help. But you need to act now.\\r\\nLet\\u2019s get this done. You\\u2019ve got this!\",\"third-essay\":\"While I have not yet had the opportunity to participate in formal academic research or publish a paper, I have taken several steps toward building a strong foundation for a future in scientific inquiry. My primary interests lie at the intersection of computer science, artificial intelligence, and sustainable technology. These areas have consistently shaped my self-driven learning, extracurricular activities, and academic aspirations.\\r\\nI have participated in global STEM programs such as the AFS Global STEM Accelerators, The Junior Academy of the New York Academy of Sciences, and the 1000 Girls 1000 Futures program, where I collaborated with international peers on real-world challenges. For example, through The Junior Academy, I worked with a team on a project named HAWK, which focused on environmental awareness and sustainable urban living. This experience gave me insight into how research-based teamwork can drive meaningful innovation.\\r\\nAs the founder of my school\\u2019s robotics club and editor of our science magazine, I\\u2019ve d platforms that promote curiosity, peer collaboration, and scientific thinking. I also participated in an Erasmus+ KA210 project focused on smart cities, which introduced me to urban research frameworks and international cooperation.\\r\\nI see research not just as a method, but as a mindset\\u2014and I am committed to growing through hands-on projects and academic mentorship. My next goal is to actively contribute to research that bridges technology and social impact.\",\"hours_commitment\":\"\",\"time_blocks\":\"\",\"hear_about\":\"\"}', '[]', '2025-07-02 12:04:33'),
