('SYSJ0425', '{\"full_name\":\"Yaseen Saad\",\"email-address\":\"yaseen.saad.front.end@gmail.com\",\"contact-number\":\"01033553865\",\"country\":\"Egypt\",\"birth-date\":\"2008-03-11\",\"institution\":\"STEM High School for Boys - 6th of October\",\"grade-year\":\"12\",\"gpa\":\"1.0\",\"interest\":\"Biology\",\"grade-previous\":\"My research background is mostly in theoretical physics and computational science, focusing on applying advanced algorithms to complex scientific problems. My expertise spans computational physics, computational astrophysics, and computational chemistry. A significant aspect of my experience comes from my schools Capstone program, where Ive maintained a streak of A+ grades across all four past semesters. These projects have allowed me to apply theoretical knowledge to practical challenges, such as developing a hydrogen heater, which was a heater that generates electricity and heats up water using only wasted soda cans. Furthermore, as a Capstone Assistant, I guided 5 teams, and their projects collectively earned half of all A+ grades awarded across the entire school. My involvement as a Junior Researcher at the Youth Science Journal last year focused on computational astrophysics. My project specifically involved proposing a machine learning method to predict star death scenarios, aiming to address a literature gap in dynamic stellar evolution modeling. This work, though still in its data training phase, has significantly deepened my understanding of predictive modeling and large-scale data analysis in scientific contexts. Beyond these projects, Ive actively engaged in applied computational research. As a founder and organizer of the first Computational Science Olympiad in Egypt, Ive designed and implemented platforms that challenge students with complex scientific computing problems. These experiences, combining rigorous theoretical study with practical computational application and the development of platforms for scientific engagement, have prepared me to contribute to YSJs high standards of innovative research.\",\"first-essay\":\"My research background is mostly in theoretical physics and computational science, focusing on applying advanced algorithms to complex scientific problems. My expertise spans computational physics, computational astrophysics, and computational chemistry.\\r\\nA significant aspect of my experience comes from my schools Capstone program, where Ive maintained a streak of A+ grades across all four past semesters. These projects have allowed me to apply theoretical knowledge to practical challenges, such as developing a hydrogen heater, which was a heater that generates electricity and heats up water using only wasted soda cans. Furthermore, as a Capstone Assistant, I guided 5 teams, and their projects collectively earned half of all A+ grades awarded across the entire school.\\r\\nMy involvement as a Junior Researcher at the Youth Science Journal last year focused on computational astrophysics. My project specifically involved proposing a machine learning method to predict star death scenarios, aiming to address a literature gap in dynamic stellar evolution modeling. This work, though still in its data training phase, has significantly deepened my understanding of predictive modeling and large-scale data analysis in scientific contexts.\\r\\nBeyond these projects, Ive actively engaged in applied computational research. As a founder and organizer of the first Computational Science Olympiad in Egypt, Ive designed and implemented platforms that challenge students with complex scientific computing problems.\\r\\nThese experiences, combining rigorous theoretical study with practical computational application and the development of platforms for scientific engagement, have prepared me to contribute to YSJs high standards of innovative research.\",\"second-essay\":\"My research background is mostly in theoretical physics and computational science, focusing on applying advanced alg